# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cosmology
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The **Big Bang** is a physical theory that describes how the universe expanded from an initial state of high density and temperature.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Various cosmological models based on the Big Bang concept explain a broad range of phenomena, including the abundance of light elements, the cosmic microwave background (CMB) radiation, the redshift of galaxies and the large-scale structure of the universe.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The observed uniformity of the universe, which leads to the horizon and flatness problems, is explained through cosmic inflation: a phase of accelerated expansion during the earliest stages.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Detailed measurements of the expansion rate of the universe place the initial singularity at an estimated 13.787±0.02 billion years ago, which is considered the age of the universe.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] A wide range of empirical evidence strongly favors the Big Bang event, which is now widely accepted.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Extrapolating this cosmic expansion backward in time using the known laws of physics, the models describe an extraordinarily hot and dense primordial universe.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Physics lacks a widely accepted theory that can model the earliest conditions of the Big Bang.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] As the universe expanded, it cooled sufficiently to allow the formation of subatomic particles, and later atoms.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] These primordial elements—mostly hydrogen, with some helium and lithium—then coalesced under the force of gravity aided by dark matter, forming early stars and galaxies.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Measurements of the redshifts of supernovae indicate that the expansion of the universe is accelerating, an observation attributed to a concept called dark energy.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The concept of an expanding universe was introduced by the physicist Alexander Friedmann in 1922 with the mathematical derivation of the Friedmann equations.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The earliest empirical observation of an expanding universe is known as Hubble's law, published in work by physicist Edwin Hubble in 1929, which discerned that galaxies are moving away from Earth at a rate that accelerates proportionally with distance.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Independent of Friedmann's work, and independent of Hubble's observations, in 1931 physicist Georges Lemaître proposed that the universe emerged from a "primeval atom", introducing the modern notion of the Big Bang.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] In 1964, the CMB was accidentally discovered.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Over the next few years measurements showed this radiation to be uniform over directions in the sky and the shape of the energy versus intensity curve, both consistent with the Big Bang models of high temperatures and densities in the distant past.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] By the late 1960s most cosmologists were convinced that competing steady-state model of cosmic evolution was incorrect.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] There remain aspects of the observed universe that are not yet adequately explained by the Big Bang models.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] These include the unequal abundances of matter and antimatter known as baryon asymmetry, the detailed nature of dark matter surrounding galaxies, and the origin of dark energy.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Big Bang cosmology models depend on three major assumptions: the universality of physical laws, the cosmological principle, and that the matter content can be modeled as a perfect fluid.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The universality of physical laws is one of the underlying principles of the theory of relativity.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The cosmological principle states that on large scales the universe is homogeneous and isotropic—appearing the same in all directions regardless of location.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] A perfect fluid has no viscosity; the pressure of a perfect fluid is proportional to its density.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] These ideas were initially taken as postulates, but later efforts were made to test each of them.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] For example, the first assumption has been tested by observations showing that the largest possible deviation of the fine-structure constant over much of the age of the universe is of order 10−5.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The key physical law behind these models, general relativity has passed stringent tests on the scale of the Solar System and binary stars.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The cosmological principle has been confirmed to a level of 10−5 via observations of the temperature of the CMB.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] At the scale of the CMB horizon, the universe has been measured to be homogeneous with an upper bound on the order of 10% inhomogeneity, as of 1995.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The cosmological principle dramatically simplifies the equations of general relativity, giving the Friedmann–Lemaître–Robertson–Walker metric to describe the geometry of the universe and, with the assumption of a perfect fluid, the Friedmann equations giving the time dependence of that geometry.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The only parameter at this level of description is the mass-energy density: the geometry of the universe and its expansion is a direct consequence of its density.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] All of the major features of Big Bang cosmology are related to these results.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] In Big Bang cosmology, the mass–energy density controls the shape and evolution of the universe.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] By combining astronomical observations with known laws of thermodynamics and particle physics, cosmologists have worked out the components of the density over the lifespan of the universe.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] In the current universe, luminous matter, the stars, planets, and so on makes up less than 5% of the density.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Dark matter accounts for 27% and dark energy the remaining 68%.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] An important feature of the Big Bang spacetime is the presence of particle horizons.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Since the universe has a finite age, and light travels at a finite speed, there may be events in the past whose light has not yet had time to reach earth.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] This places a limit or a *past horizon* on the most distant objects that can be observed.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Conversely, because space is expanding, and more distant objects are receding ever more quickly, light emitted by us today may never "catch up" to very distant objects.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] This defines a *future horizon*, which limits the events in the future that we will be able to influence.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The presence of either type of horizon depends on the details of the Friedmann–Lemaître–Robertson–Walker (FLRW) metric that describes the expansion of the universe.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Our understanding of the universe back to very early times suggests that there is a past horizon, though in practice our view is also limited by the opacity of the universe at early times.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] So our view cannot extend further backward in time, though the horizon recedes in space.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] If the expansion of the universe continues to accelerate, there is a future horizon as well.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Some processes in the early universe occurred too slowly, compared to the expansion rate of the universe, to reach approximate thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Others were fast enough to reach thermalization.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The parameter usually used to find out whether a process in the very early universe has reached thermal equilibrium is the ratio between the rate of the process (usually rate of collisions between particles) and the Hubble parameter.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The larger the ratio, the more time particles had to thermalize before they were too far away from each other.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] According to the Big Bang models, the universe at the beginning was very hot and very compact, and since then it has been expanding and cooling.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Existing theories of physics cannot tell us about the moment of the Big Bang.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Extrapolation of the expansion of the universe backwards in time using only classical general relativity yields a gravitational singularity with infinite density and temperature at a finite time in the past.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] However this classical gravitational theory is expected to be inadequate to describe physics under these conditions.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Thus the meaning of this singularity in the context of the Big Bang is unclear.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The earliest time that general relativity can be applied is called the Planck time.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Earlier, during the Planck epoch, when the temperature of the universe was close to the Planck scale (around 1032 K or 1028 eV) quantum gravity effects are expected to be dominant.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] To date there is no accepted theory of quantum gravity; above the Planck energy scale, undiscovered physics could influence the expansion history of the universe.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The earliest phases of the Big Bang are subject to much speculation, given the lack of available data.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] In the most common models the universe was filled homogeneously and isotropically with a very high energy density and huge temperatures and pressures, and was very rapidly expanding and cooling.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The period up to 10−43 seconds into the expansion, the Planck epoch, was a phase in which the four fundamental forces—the electromagnetic force, the strong nuclear force, the weak nuclear force, and the gravitational force—were unified as one.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] In this stage, the characteristic scale length of the universe was the Planck length, 1.6×10−35 m, and consequently had a temperature of approximately 1032 degrees Celsius.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Even the very concept of a particle breaks down in these conditions.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] A proper understanding of this period awaits the development of a theory of quantum gravity.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The Planck epoch was succeeded by the grand unification epoch beginning at 10−43 seconds, where gravitation separated from the other forces as the universe's temperature fell.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] At approximately 10−37 seconds into the expansion, a phase transition caused a cosmic inflation, during which the universe grew exponentially, unconstrained by the light speed invariance, and temperatures dropped by a factor of 100,000.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] This concept is motivated by the flatness problem, where the density of matter and energy is very close to the critical density needed to produce a flat universe.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] That is, the shape of the universe has no overall geometric curvature due to gravitational influence.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Microscopic quantum fluctuations that occurred because of Heisenberg's uncertainty principle were "frozen in" by inflation, becoming amplified into the seeds that would later form the large-scale structure of the universe.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] At a time around 10−36 seconds, the electroweak epoch begins when the strong nuclear force separates from the other forces, with only the electromagnetic force and weak nuclear force remaining unified.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] All of the mass-energy in all of the galaxies currently visible started in a sphere with a radius around 4 × 10−29 m then grew to a sphere with a radius around 0.9 m by the end of inflation.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Reheating followed as the inflaton field decayed, until the universe obtained the temperatures required for the production of a quark–gluon plasma as well as all other elementary particles.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Temperatures were so high that the random motions of particles were at relativistic speeds, and particle–antiparticle pairs of all kinds were being continuously created and destroyed in collisions.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] At some point, an unknown reaction called baryogenesis violated the conservation of baryon number, leading to a very small excess of quarks and leptons over antiquarks and antileptons—of the order of one part in 30 million.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] This resulted in the predominance of matter over antimatter in the present universe.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The universe continued to decrease in density and fall in temperature, hence the typical energy of each particle was decreasing.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Symmetry-breaking phase transitions put the fundamental forces of physics and the parameters of elementary particles into their present form, with the electromagnetic force and weak nuclear force separating at about 10−12 seconds.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] After about 10−11 seconds, the picture becomes less speculative, since particle energies drop to values that can be attained in particle accelerators.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] At about 10−6 seconds, quarks and gluons combined to form baryons such as protons and neutrons.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The small excess of quarks over antiquarks led to a small excess of baryons over antibaryons.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The temperature was no longer high enough to create either new proton–antiproton or neutron–antineutron pairs.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] A mass annihilation immediately followed, leaving just one in 108 of the original matter particles and none of their antiparticles.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] A similar process happened at about 1 second for electrons and positrons.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] After these annihilations, the remaining protons, neutrons and electrons were no longer moving relativistically and the energy density of the universe was dominated by photons (with a minor contribution from neutrinos).
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Most protons remained uncombined as hydrogen nuclei.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] As the universe cooled, the rest energy density of matter came to gravitationally dominate over that of the photon and neutrino radiation at a time of about 50,000 years.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] At a time of about 380,000 years, the universe cooled enough that electrons and nuclei combined into neutral atoms (mostly hydrogen) in an event called recombination.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] This process made the previously opaque universe transparent, and the photons that last scattered during this epoch comprise the cosmic microwave background.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] After the recombination epoch, the slightly denser regions of the uniformly distributed matter gravitationally attracted nearby matter and thus grew even denser, forming gas clouds, stars, galaxies, and the other astronomical structures observable today.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The details of this process depend on the amount and type of matter in the universe.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The four possible types of matter are known as cold dark matter (CDM), warm dark matter, hot dark matter, and baryonic matter.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The best measurements available, from the Wilkinson Microwave Anisotropy Probe (WMAP), show that the data is well-fit by a Lambda-CDM model in which dark matter is assumed to be cold.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] This CDM is estimated to make up about 23% of the matter/energy of the universe, while baryonic matter makes up about 4.6%.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Independent lines of evidence from Type Ia supernovae and the CMB imply that the universe today is dominated by a mysterious form of energy known as dark energy, which appears to homogeneously permeate all of space.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Observations suggest that 73% of the total energy density of the present day universe is in this form.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] When the universe was very young it was likely infused with dark energy, but with everything closer together, gravity predominated, braking the expansion.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Eventually, after billions of years of expansion, the declining density of matter relative to the density of dark energy allowed the expansion of the universe to begin to accelerate.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Dark energy in its simplest formulation is modeled by a cosmological constant term in Einstein field equations of general relativity, but its composition and mechanism are unknown.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] More generally, the details of its equation of state and relationship with the Standard Model of particle physics continue to be investigated both through observation and theory.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] All of this cosmic evolution after the inflationary epoch can be rigorously described and modeled by the lambda-CDM model of cosmology, which uses the independent frameworks of quantum mechanics and general relativity.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] There are no easily testable models that would describe the situation prior to approximately 10−15 seconds.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Understanding this earliest of eras in the history of the universe is one of the greatest unsolved problems in physics.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The term *Big Bang* did not catch on until the 1970s.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] It is popularly reported that Hoyle, who favored the steady state, intended this to be pejorative, but Hoyle explicitly denied this and said it was just a striking image meant to highlight the difference between the two models.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Helge Kragh writes that the evidence for the claim that it was meant as a pejorative is "unconvincing", and mentions a number of indications that it was not a pejorative.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] A primordial singularity is sometimes called "the Big Bang", but the term can also refer to a more generic early hot, dense phase.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The term itself has been argued to be a misnomer because it evokes an explosion.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The argument is that whereas an explosion suggests expansion into a surrounding space, the Big Bang only describes the intrinsic expansion of the contents of the universe.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Another issue pointed out by Santhosh Mathew is that bang implies sound, which is not an important feature of the model.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] However, when Sky and Telescope ran a competition in 1993 to find a more suitable alternative no alternative was successful.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] is the small box to the left of, and nearly below, the Moon) – several thousand galaxies, each consisting of billions of stars, are in this small view.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] – the universe is estimated to contain 200 billion galaxies.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Early cosmological models developed from observations of the structure of the universe and from theoretical considerations.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] In 1912, Vesto Slipher measured the first Doppler shift of a "spiral nebula" (spiral nebula is the obsolete term for spiral galaxies), and soon discovered that almost all such nebulae were receding from Earth.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] He did not grasp the cosmological implications of this fact, and indeed at the time it was highly controversial whether or not these nebulae were "island universes" outside our Milky Way.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Ten years later, Alexander Friedmann, a Russian cosmologist and mathematician, derived the Friedmann equations from the Einstein field equations, showing that the universe might be expanding in contrast to the static universe model advocated by Albert Einstein at that time.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] In 1924, American astronomer Edwin Hubble's measurement of the great distance to the nearest spiral nebulae showed that these systems were indeed other galaxies.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Starting that same year, Hubble painstakingly developed a series of distance indicators, the forerunner of the cosmic distance ladder, using the 100-inch (2.5 m) Hooker telescope at Mount Wilson Observatory.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] This allowed him to estimate distances to galaxies whose redshifts had already been measured, mostly by Slipher.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] In 1929, Hubble, with the help of Milton Humason, discovered a correlation between distance and recessional velocity—now known as Hubble's law.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Independently deriving Friedmann's equations in 1927, Georges Lemaître, a Belgian physicist and Roman Catholic priest, proposed that the recession of the nebulae was due to the expansion of the universe.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] He inferred the relation that Hubble would later observe, given the cosmological principle.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] In the 1920s and 1930s, almost every major cosmologist preferred an eternal steady-state universe, and several complained that the beginning of time implied by an expanding universe imported religious concepts into physics; this objection was later repeated by supporters of the steady-state theory.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] This perception was enhanced by the fact that the originator of the expanding universe concept, Lemaître, was a Roman Catholic priest.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Arthur Eddington agreed with Aristotle that the universe did not have a beginning in time, *viz*., that matter is eternal.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] A beginning in time was "repugnant" to him.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] During the 1930s, other ideas were proposed as non-standard cosmologies to explain Hubble's observations, including the Milne model, the oscillatory universe (originally suggested by Friedmann, but advocated by Albert Einstein and Richard C.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Tolman) and Fritz Zwicky's tired light hypothesis.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] After World War II, two distinct possibilities emerged.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] One was Fred Hoyle's steady-state model, whereby new matter would be created as the universe seemed to expand.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] In this model the universe is roughly the same at any point in time.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The other was Lemaître's expanding universe theory, advocated and developed by George Gamow, who used it to develop a theory for the abundance of chemical elements in the universe. and whose associates, Ralph Alpher and Robert Herman, predicted the cosmic background radiation.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Ironically, it was Hoyle who coined the phrase that came to be applied to Lemaître's theory, referring to it as "this *big bang* idea" during a BBC Radio broadcast in March 1949.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] For a while, support was split between these two theories.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Eventually, the observational evidence, most notably from radio source counts, began to favor Big Bang over steady state.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The discovery and confirmation of the CMB in 1964 secured the Big Bang as the best theory of the origin and evolution of the universe.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] In 1968 and 1970, Roger Penrose, Stephen Hawking, and George F.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Ellis published papers where they showed that mathematical singularities were an inevitable initial condition of relativistic models of the Big Bang.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Then, from the 1970s to the 1990s, cosmologists worked on characterizing the features of the Big Bang universe and resolving outstanding problems.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] In 1981, Alan Guth made a breakthrough in theoretical work on resolving certain outstanding theoretical problems in the Big Bang models with the introduction of an epoch of rapid expansion in the early universe he called "inflation".
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Significant progress in Big Bang cosmology has been made since the late 1990s as a result of advances in telescope technology as well as the analysis of data from satellites such as the Cosmic Background Explorer (COBE), the Hubble Space Telescope and WMAP.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Cosmologists now have fairly precise and accurate measurements of many of the parameters of the Big Bang model, and have made the unexpected discovery that the expansion of the universe appears to be accelerating.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The Big Bang models offer a comprehensive explanation for a broad range of observed phenomena, including the abundances of the light elements, the cosmic microwave background, large-scale structure, and Hubble's law.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] More recent evidence includes observations of galaxy formation and evolution, and the distribution of large-scale cosmic structures.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] These are sometimes called the "four pillars" of the Big Bang models.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Precise modern models of the Big Bang appeal to various exotic physical phenomena that have not been observed in terrestrial laboratory experiments or incorporated into the Standard Model of particle physics.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Of these features, dark matter is currently the subject of most active laboratory investigations.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Remaining issues include the cuspy halo problem and the dwarf galaxy problem of cold dark matter.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Dark energy is also an area of intense interest for scientists, but it is not clear whether direct detection of dark energy will be possible.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Inflation and baryogenesis remain more speculative features of current Big Bang models.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Viable, quantitative explanations for such phenomena are still being sought.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Observations of distant galaxies and quasars show that these objects are redshifted: the light emitted from them has been shifted to longer wavelengths.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] This can be seen by taking a frequency spectrum of an object and matching the spectroscopic pattern of emission or absorption lines corresponding to atoms of the chemical elements interacting with the light.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] These redshifts are uniformly isotropic, distributed evenly among the observed objects in all directions.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] If the redshift is interpreted as a Doppler shift, the recessional velocity of the object can be calculated.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] For some galaxies, it is possible to estimate distances via the cosmic distance ladder.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Hubble's law implies that the universe is uniformly expanding everywhere.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] This cosmic expansion was predicted from general relativity by Friedmann in 1922 and Lemaître in 1927, well before Hubble made his 1929 analysis and observations, and it remains the cornerstone of the Big Bang model as developed by Friedmann, Lemaître, Robertson, and Walker.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The theory requires the relation $v=HD$ to hold at all times, where D is the proper distance, v is the recessional velocity, and v , H , and D vary as the universe expands (hence we write $H_{0}$ to denote the present-day Hubble "constant").
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] For distances much smaller than the size of the observable universe, the Hubble redshift can be thought of as the Doppler shift corresponding to the recession velocity v .
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] For distances comparable to the size of the observable universe, the attribution of the cosmological redshift becomes more ambiguous, although its interpretation as a kinematic Doppler shift remains the most natural one.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] An unexplained discrepancy between alternative determinations of the Hubble constant is known as Hubble tension.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Techniques based on observation of the CMB suggest a lower value of this constant compared to the quantity derived from measurements based on the cosmic distance ladder.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] In 1964, Arno Penzias and Robert Wilson serendipitously discovered the cosmic background radiation, an omnidirectional signal in the microwave band.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Their discovery provided substantial confirmation of the big-bang predictions by Alpher, Herman and Gamow around 1950.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Through the 1970s, the radiation was found to be approximately consistent with a blackbody spectrum in all directions; this spectrum has been redshifted by the expansion of the universe, and today corresponds to approximately 2.725 K.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] This tipped the balance of evidence in favor of the Big Bang model, and Penzias and Wilson were awarded the 1978 Nobel Prize in Physics.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The *surface of last scattering* corresponding to emission of the CMB occurs shortly after *recombination*, the epoch when neutral hydrogen becomes stable.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Prior to this, the universe comprised a hot dense photon-baryon plasma sea where photons were quickly scattered from free charged particles.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Peaking at around 372±14 kyr, the mean free path for a photon becomes long enough to reach the present day and the universe becomes transparent.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Mather and George Smoot were awarded the 2006 Nobel Prize in Physics for their leadership in these results.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] During the following decade, CMB anisotropies were further investigated by a large number of ground-based and balloon experiments.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] In 2000–2001, several experiments, most notably BOOMERanG, found the shape of the universe to be spatially almost flat by measuring the typical angular size (the size on the sky) of the anisotropies.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] In early 2003, the first results of the Wilkinson Microwave Anisotropy Probe were released, yielding what were at the time the most accurate values for some of the cosmological parameters.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The results disproved several specific cosmic inflation models, but are consistent with the inflation theory in general.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The *Planck* space probe was launched in May 2009.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Other ground and balloon-based cosmic microwave background experiments are ongoing.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Using Big Bang models, it is possible to calculate the expected concentration of the isotopes helium-4 (4He), helium-3 (3He), deuterium (2H), and lithium-7 (7Li) in the universe as ratios to the amount of ordinary hydrogen.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The relative abundances depend on a single parameter, the ratio of photons to baryons.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] This value can be calculated independently from the detailed structure of CMB fluctuations.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The ratios predicted (by mass, not by abundance) are about 0.25 for 4He:H, about 10−3 for 2H:H, about 10−4 for 3He:H, and about 10−9 for 7Li:H.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The measured abundances all agree at least roughly with those predicted from a single value of the baryon-to-photon ratio.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The agreement is excellent for deuterium, close but formally discrepant for 4He, and off by a factor of two for 7Li (this anomaly is known as the cosmological lithium problem); in the latter two cases, there are substantial systematic uncertainties.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Nonetheless, the general consistency with abundances predicted by BBN is strong evidence for the Big Bang, as the theory is the only known explanation for the relative abundances of light elements, and it is virtually impossible to "tune" the Big Bang to produce much more or less than 20–30% helium.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Detailed observations of the morphology and distribution of galaxies and quasars are in agreement with the current Big Bang models.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] A combination of observations and theory suggest that the first quasars and galaxies formed within a billion years after the Big Bang, and since then, larger structures have been forming, such as galaxy clusters and superclusters.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Populations of stars have been aging and evolving, so that distant galaxies (which are observed as they were in the early universe) appear very different from nearby galaxies (observed in a more recent state).
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Moreover, galaxies that formed relatively recently appear markedly different from galaxies formed at similar distances but shortly after the Big Bang.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] These observations are strong arguments against the steady-state model.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Observations of star formation, galaxy and quasar distributions and larger structures, agree well with Big Bang simulations of the formation of structure in the universe, and are helping to complete details of the theory.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] In 2011, astronomers found what they believe to be pristine clouds of primordial gas by analyzing absorption lines in the spectra of distant quasars.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Before this discovery, all other astronomical objects have been observed to contain heavy elements that are formed in stars.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Despite being sensitive to carbon, oxygen, and silicon, these three elements were not detected in these two clouds.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Since the clouds of gas have no detectable levels of heavy elements, they likely formed in the first few minutes after the Big Bang, during BBN.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The age of the universe as estimated from the Hubble expansion and the CMB is now in agreement with other estimates using the ages of the oldest stars, both as measured by applying the theory of stellar evolution to globular clusters and through radiometric dating of individual Population II stars.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] It is also in agreement with age estimates based on measurements of the expansion using Type Ia supernovae and measurements of temperature fluctuations in the cosmic microwave background.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The agreement of independent measurements of this age supports the Lambda-CDM (ΛCDM) model, since the model is used to relate some of the measurements to an age estimate, and all estimates turn agree.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Still, some observations of objects from the relatively early universe (in particular quasar APM 08279+5255) raise concern as to whether these objects had enough time to form so early in the ΛCDM model.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The prediction that the CMB temperature was higher in the past has been experimentally supported by observations of very low temperature absorption lines in gas clouds at high redshift.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] This prediction also implies that the amplitude of the Sunyaev–Zel'dovich effect in clusters of galaxies does not depend directly on redshift.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Observations have found this to be roughly true, but this effect depends on cluster properties that do change with cosmic time, making precise measurements difficult.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Future gravitational-wave observatories might be able to detect primordial gravitational waves, relics of the early universe, up to less than a second after the Big Bang.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] As with any theory, a number of mysteries and problems have arisen as a result of the development of the Big Bang models.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Some of these mysteries and problems have been resolved while others are still outstanding.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Proposed solutions to some of the problems in the Big Bang model have revealed new mysteries of their own.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] For example, the horizon problem, the magnetic monopole problem, and the flatness problem are most commonly resolved with inflation theory, but the details of the inflationary universe are still left unresolved and many, including some founders of the theory, say it has been disproven.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] What follows are a list of the mysterious aspects of the Big Bang concept still under intense investigation by cosmologists and astrophysicists.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] It is not yet understood why the universe has more matter than antimatter.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] It is generally assumed that when the universe was young and very hot it was in statistical equilibrium and contained equal numbers of baryons and antibaryons.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Both matter and antimatter were much more abundant than today, with a tiny asymmetry of only one part in 10 billion.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The matter and antimatter collided and annihilated, leaving only the residual amount of matter.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Today observations suggest that the universe, including its most distant parts, is made almost entirely of normal matter with very little antimatter.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] If matter and antimatter were in complete symmetry, then annihilation would result in only photons and virtually no matter at all, which is obviously not what is observed.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] A process called baryogenesis was hypothesized to account for the asymmetry.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] For baryogenesis to occur, the Sakharov conditions must be satisfied.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] These require that baryon number is not conserved, that C-symmetry and CP-symmetry are violated and that the universe depart from thermodynamic equilibrium.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] All these conditions occur in the Standard Model, but the effects are not strong enough to explain the present baryon asymmetry.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Measurements of the redshift–magnitude relation for type Ia supernovae indicate that the expansion of the universe has been accelerating since the universe was about half its present age.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] To explain this acceleration, cosmological models require that much of the energy in the universe consists of a component with large negative pressure, dubbed "dark energy".
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Dark energy, though speculative, solves numerous problems.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Measurements of the cosmic microwave background indicate that the universe is very nearly spatially flat, and therefore according to general relativity the universe must have almost exactly the critical density of mass/energy.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] But the mass density of the universe can be measured from its gravitational clustering, and is found to have only about 30% of the critical density.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Since theory suggests that dark energy does not cluster in the usual way it is the best explanation for the "missing" energy density.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Dark energy also helps to explain two geometrical measures of the overall curvature of the universe, one using the frequency of gravitational lenses, and the other using baryon acoustic oscillations, the characteristic pattern of the large-scale structure, as a cosmic ruler.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Negative pressure is believed to be a property of vacuum energy, but the exact nature and existence of dark energy remains one of the great mysteries of the Big Bang.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Results from the WMAP team in 2008 are in accordance with a universe that consists of 73% dark energy, 23% dark matter, 4.6% regular matter and less than 1% neutrinos.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] According to theory, the energy density in matter decreases with the expansion of the universe, but the dark energy density remains constant (or nearly so) as the universe expands.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Therefore, matter made up a larger fraction of the total energy of the universe in the past than it does today, but its fractional contribution will fall in the far future as dark energy becomes even more dominant.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The dark energy component of the universe has been explained by theorists using a variety of competing theories including Einstein's cosmological constant but also extending to more exotic forms of quintessence or other modified gravity schemes.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] A cosmological constant problem, sometimes called the "most embarrassing problem in physics", results from the apparent discrepancy between the measured energy density of dark energy, and the one naively predicted from Planck units.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] During the 1970s and the 1980s, various observations showed that there is not sufficient visible matter in the universe to account for the apparent strength of gravitational forces within and between galaxies.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] This led to the idea that up to 90% of the matter in the universe is dark matter that does not emit light or interact with normal baryonic matter.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] In addition, the assumption that the universe is mostly normal matter led to predictions that were strongly inconsistent with observations.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] In particular, the universe today is far more lumpy and contains far less deuterium than can be accounted for without dark matter.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] While dark matter has always been controversial, it is inferred by various observations: the anisotropies in the CMB, the galaxy rotation problem, galaxy cluster velocity dispersions, large-scale structure distributions, gravitational lensing studies, and X-ray measurements of galaxy clusters.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Indirect evidence for dark matter comes from its gravitational influence on other matter, as no dark matter particles have been observed in laboratories.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Many particle physics candidates for dark matter have been proposed, and several projects to detect them directly are underway.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Additionally, there are outstanding problems associated with the currently favored cold dark matter model which include the dwarf galaxy problem and the cuspy halo problem.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Alternative theories have been proposed that do not require a large amount of undetected matter, but instead modify the laws of gravity established by Newton and Einstein; yet no alternative theory has been as successful as the cold dark matter proposal in explaining all extant observations.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The horizon problem results from the premise that information cannot travel faster than light.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] In a universe of finite age this sets a limit—the particle horizon—on the separation of any two regions of space that are in causal contact.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The observed isotropy of the CMB is problematic in this regard: if the universe had been dominated by radiation or matter at all times up to the epoch of last scattering, the particle horizon at that time would correspond to about 2 degrees on the sky.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] There would then be no mechanism to cause wider regions to have the same temperature.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] A resolution to this apparent inconsistency is offered by inflation theory in which a homogeneous and isotropic scalar energy field dominates the universe at some very early period (before baryogenesis).
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] During inflation, the universe undergoes exponential expansion, and the particle horizon expands much more rapidly than previously assumed, so that regions presently on opposite sides of the observable universe are well inside each other's particle horizon.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The observed isotropy of the CMB then follows from the fact that this larger region was in causal contact before the beginning of inflation.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Heisenberg's uncertainty principle predicts that during the inflationary phase there would be quantum thermal fluctuations, which would be magnified to a cosmic scale.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] These fluctuations served as the seeds for all the current structures in the universe.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Inflation predicts that the primordial fluctuations are nearly scale invariant and Gaussian, which has been confirmed by measurements of the CMB.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The magnetic monopole objection was raised in the late 1970s.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Grand unified theories (GUTs) predicted topological defects in space that would manifest as magnetic monopoles.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] These objects would be produced efficiently in the hot early universe, resulting in a density much higher than is consistent with observations, given that no monopoles have been found.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] This problem is resolved by cosmic inflation, which removes all point defects from the observable universe, in the same way that it drives the geometry to flatness.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The flatness problem (also known as the oldness problem) is an observational problem associated with a FLRW.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The universe may have positive, negative, or zero spatial curvature depending on its total energy density.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Curvature is negative if its density is less than the critical density; positive if greater; and zero at the critical density, in which case space is said to be *flat*.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Observations indicate the universe is consistent with being flat.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] The problem is that any small departure from the critical density grows with time, and yet the universe today remains very close to flat.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Given that a natural timescale for departure from flatness might be the Planck time, 10−43 seconds, the fact that the universe has reached neither a heat death nor a Big Crunch after billions of years requires an explanation.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] For instance, even at the relatively late age of a few minutes (the time of nucleosynthesis), the density of the universe must have been within one part in 1014 of its critical value, or it would not exist as it does today.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] In addition to confusion about the nature of cosmic expansion, the Big Bang model itself is sometimes misunderstood.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] One of the common misconceptions about the Big Bang model is that it fully explains the origin of the universe.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] However, the Big Bang model does not describe how energy, time, and space were caused, but rather it describes the emergence of the present universe from an ultra-dense and high-temperature initial state.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Another common misconception relates to the recession speeds associated with Hubble's law.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] These are not velocities in a relativistic sense (for example, they are not related to the spatial components of 4-velocities).
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Therefore, it is not remarkable that according to Hubble's law, galaxies farther than the Hubble distance recede faster than the speed of light.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p01] Such recession speeds do not correspond to faster-than-light travel.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] Given current understanding, scientific extrapolations about the future of the universe are only possible for finite durations, albeit for much longer periods than the current age of the universe.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] Anything beyond that becomes increasingly speculative.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] Likewise, at present, a proper understanding of the origin of the universe can only be subject to conjecture.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] The Big Bang explains the evolution of the universe from a starting density and temperature that is well beyond humanity's capability to replicate, so extrapolations to the most extreme conditions and earliest times are necessarily more speculative.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] Lemaître called this initial state the "*primeval atom*" while Gamow called the material "*ylem*".
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] How the initial state of the universe originated is still an open question, but the Big Bang model does constrain some of its characteristics.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] For example, if specific laws of nature were to come to existence in a random way, inflation models show, some combinations of these are far more probable, partly explaining why our Universe is rather stable.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] Another possible explanation for the stability of the Universe could be a hypothetical multiverse, which assumes every possible universe to exist, and thinking species could only emerge in those stable enough.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] A flat universe implies a balance between gravitational potential energy and other energy forms, requiring no additional energy to be created.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] The Big Bang theory is built upon the equations of classical general relativity, which are not expected to be valid at the origin of cosmic time, as the temperature of the universe approaches the Planck scale.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] Correcting this will require the development of a correct treatment of quantum gravity.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] Certain quantum gravity treatments, such as the Wheeler–DeWitt equation, imply that time itself could be an emergent property.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] As such, physics may conclude that time did not exist before the Big Bang.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] While it is not known what could have preceded the hot dense state of the early universe or how and why it originated, or even whether such questions are sensible, speculation abounds on the subject of "cosmogony".
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] Proposals in the last two categories see the Big Bang as an event in either a much larger and older universe or in a multiverse.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] Before observations of dark energy, cosmologists considered two scenarios for the future of the universe.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] If the mass density of the universe were greater than the critical density, then the universe would reach a maximum size and then begin to collapse.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] It would become denser and hotter again, ending with a state similar to that in which it started—a Big Crunch.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] Alternatively, if the density in the universe were equal to or below the critical density, the expansion would slow down but never stop.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] Star formation would cease with the consumption of interstellar gas in each galaxy; stars would burn out, leaving white dwarfs, neutron stars, and black holes.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] Collisions between these would result in mass accumulating into larger and larger black holes.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] The average temperature of the universe would very gradually asymptotically approach absolute zero—a Big Freeze.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] Moreover, if protons are unstable, then baryonic matter would disappear, leaving only radiation and black holes.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] Eventually, black holes would evaporate by emitting Hawking radiation.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] The entropy of the universe would increase to the point where no organized form of energy could be extracted from it, a scenario known as heat death.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] Modern observations of accelerating expansion imply that more and more of the currently visible universe will pass beyond our event horizon and out of contact with us.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] The Lambda-CDM model of the universe contains dark energy in the form of a cosmological constant.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] This theory suggests that only gravitationally bound systems, such as galaxies, will remain together, and they too will be subject to heat death as the universe expands and cools.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] Other explanations of dark energy, called phantom dark energy theories, suggest that ultimately galaxy clusters, stars, planets, atoms, nuclei, and matter itself will be torn apart by the ever-increasing expansion in a so-called Big Rip.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] As a description of the origin of the universe, the Big Bang has significant bearing on religion and philosophy.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] As a result, it has become one of the liveliest areas in the discourse between science and religion.
[src:cosmology/big-bang-p02] Some believe the Big Bang implies a creator, while others argue that Big Bang cosmology makes the notion of a creator superfluous.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The **cosmic microwave background** (**CMB**, **CMBR**), or **relic radiation**, is microwave radiation that fills all space in the observable universe.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] With a standard optical telescope, the background space between stars and galaxies is almost completely dark.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] However, a sufficiently sensitive radio telescope detects a faint background glow that is almost uniform and is not associated with any star, galaxy, or other object.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] This glow is strongest in the microwave region of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Its energy density exceeds that of all the photons emitted by all the stars in the history of the universe.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The accidental discovery of the CMB in 1964 by the American radio astronomers Arno Allan Penzias and Robert Woodrow Wilson was the culmination of work initiated in the 1940s.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The CMB is the key experimental evidence of the Big Bang theory for the origin of the universe.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] In the Big Bang cosmological models, during the earliest periods, the universe was filled with an opaque fog of dense, hot plasma of sub-atomic particles.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] As the universe expanded, this plasma cooled to the point where protons and electrons combined to form neutral atoms of mostly hydrogen.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Unlike the plasma, these atoms could not scatter thermal radiation by Thomson scattering, and so the universe became transparent.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Known as the recombination epoch, this decoupling event released photons to travel freely through space.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] However, the photons have grown less energetic due to the cosmological redshift associated with the expansion of the universe.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The *surface of last scattering* refers to a shell at the right distance in space so photons are now received that were originally emitted at the time of decoupling.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The CMB is very smooth and uniform, but maps by sensitive detectors detect small but important temperature variations.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Ground and space-based experiments such as COBE, WMAP and Planck have been used to measure these temperature inhomogeneities.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The anisotropy structure is influenced by various interactions of matter and photons up to the point of decoupling, which results in a characteristic pattern of tiny ripples that varies with angular scale.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The distribution of the anisotropy across the sky has frequency components that can be represented by a power spectrum displaying a sequence of peaks and valleys.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The peak values of this spectrum hold important information about the physical properties of the early universe: the first peak determines the overall curvature of the universe, while the second and third peak detail the density of normal matter and so-called dark matter, respectively.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Extracting fine details from the CMB data can be challenging, since the emission has undergone modification by foreground features such as galaxy clusters.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The cosmic microwave background radiation is an emission of uniform black body thermal energy coming from all directions.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Intensity of the CMB is expressed in kelvin (K), the SI unit of temperature.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The CMB has a thermal black body spectrum at a temperature of 2.72548±0.00057 K.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Variations in intensity are expressed as variations in temperature.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The blackbody temperature uniquely characterizes the intensity of the radiation at all wavelengths; a measured brightness temperature at any wavelength can be converted to a blackbody temperature.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The radiation is remarkably uniform across the sky, very unlike the almost point-like structure of stars or clumps of stars in galaxies.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The radiation is isotropic to roughly one part in 25,000: the root mean square variations are just over 100 μK, after subtracting a dipole anisotropy from the Doppler shift of the background radiation.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The latter is caused by the peculiar velocity of the Sun relative to the comoving cosmic rest frame as it moves at 369.82 ± 0.11 km/s towards the constellation Crater near its boundary with the constellation Leo.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The CMB dipole and aberration at higher multipoles have been measured, consistent with galactic motion.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Despite the very small degree of anisotropy in the CMB, many aspects can be measured with high precision and such measurements are critical for cosmological theories.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] In addition to temperature anisotropy, the CMB should have an angular variation in polarization.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The polarisation at each direction in the sky has an orientation described in terms of E-mode and B-mode polarization.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The E-mode signal is a factor of 10 less strong than the temperature anisotropy; it supplements the temperature data as they are correlated.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The B-mode signal is even weaker but may contain additional cosmological data.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The anisotropy is related to physical origin of the polarisation.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Excitation of an electron by linear polarised light generates polarized light at 90 degrees to the incident direction.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] If the incoming radiation is isotropic, different incoming directions create polarizations that cancel out.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] If the incoming radiation has quadrupole anisotropy, residual polarization will be seen.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Other than the temperature and polarization anisotropy, the CMB frequency spectrum is expected to feature tiny departures from the black-body law known as spectral distortions.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] These are also at the focus of an active research effort with the hope of a first measurement within the forthcoming decades, as they contain a wealth of information about the primordial universe and the formation of structures at late time.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The CMB contains the vast majority of photons in the universe by a factor of 400 to 1; the number density of photons in the CMB is one billion times (109) the number density of matter in the universe.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The present-day energy density of CMB photons greatly exceeds that of the photons emitted by all the stars over the history of the universe.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Without the expansion of the universe to cause the cooling of the CMB, the night sky would shine as brightly as the Sun.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] In 1931, Georges Lemaître speculated that remnants of the early universe may be observable as radiation, but his candidate was cosmic rays.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Tolman showed in 1934 that expansion of the universe would cool blackbody radiation while maintaining a thermal spectrum.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The cosmic microwave background was first predicted in 1948 by Ralph Alpher and Robert Herman, in a correction they prepared for a paper by Alpher's PhD advisor George Gamow.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Alpher and Herman were able to estimate the temperature of the cosmic microwave background to be 5 K.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The first published recognition of the CMB radiation as a detectable phenomenon appeared in a brief paper by Soviet astrophysicists A.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Doroshkevich and Igor Novikov, in the spring of 1964.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] In 1964, David Todd Wilkinson and Peter Roll, Robert H.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Dicke's colleagues at Princeton University, began constructing a Dicke radiometer to measure the cosmic microwave background.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] In 1964, Arno Penzias and Robert Woodrow Wilson at the Crawford Hill location of Bell Telephone Laboratories in nearby Holmdel Township, New Jersey had built a Dicke radiometer that they intended to use for radio astronomy and satellite communication experiments.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The antenna was constructed in 1959 to support Project Echo—the National Aeronautics and Space Administration's passive communications satellites, which used large Earth orbiting aluminized plastic balloons as reflectors to bounce radio signals from one point on the Earth to another.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] On 20 May 1964 they made their first measurement clearly showing the presence of the microwave background, with their instrument having an excess 4.2K antenna temperature which they could not account for.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] After receiving a telephone call from Crawford Hill, Dicke said "Boys, we've been scooped." A meeting between the Princeton and Crawford Hill groups determined that the antenna temperature was indeed due to the microwave background.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Penzias and Wilson received the 1978 Nobel Prize in Physics for their discovery.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The interpretation of the cosmic microwave background was a controversial issue in the late 1960s.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Alternative explanations included energy from within the Solar System, from galaxies, from intergalactic plasma and from multiple extragalactic radio sources.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Two requirements would show that the microwave radiation was truly "cosmic".
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] First, the intensity vs frequency or spectrum needed to be shown to match a thermal or blackbody source.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] This was accomplished by 1968 in a series of measurements of the radiation temperature at higher and lower wavelengths.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Second, the radiation needed be shown to be isotropic, the same from all directions.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] This was also accomplished by 1970, demonstrating that this radiation was truly cosmic in origin.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] In the 1970s numerous studies showed that tiny deviations from isotropy in the CMB could result from events in the early universe.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Harrison, Peebles and Yu, and Zel'dovich realized that the early universe would require quantum inhomogeneities that would result in temperature anisotropy at the level of 10−4 or 10−5.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Rashid Sunyaev, using the alternative name *relic radiation*, calculated the observable imprint that these inhomogeneities would have on the cosmic microwave background.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] After a lull in the 1970s caused in part by the many experimental difficulties in measuring CMB at high precision, increasingly stringent limits on the anisotropy of the cosmic microwave background were set by ground-based experiments during the 1980s.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] RELIKT-1, a Soviet cosmic microwave background anisotropy experiment on board the Prognoz 9 satellite (launched 1 July 1983), gave the first upper limits on the large-scale anisotropy.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The other key event in the 1980s was the proposal by Alan Guth for cosmic inflation.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] This theory of rapid spatial expansion gave an explanation for large-scale isotropy by allowing causal connection just before the epoch of last scattering.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] With this and similar theories, detailed prediction encouraged larger and more ambitious experiments.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The NASA Cosmic Background Explorer (COBE) satellite orbited Earth in 1989–1996 detected and quantified the large-scale anisotropies at the limit of its detection capabilities.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The NASA COBE mission clearly confirmed the primary anisotropy with the Differential Microwave Radiometer instrument, publishing their findings in 1992.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The team received the Nobel Prize in physics for 2006 for this discovery.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Inspired by the COBE results, a series of ground and balloon-based experiments measured cosmic microwave background anisotropies on smaller angular scales over the next two decades.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The sensitivity of the new experiments improved dramatically, with a reduction in internal noise by three orders of magnitude.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The primary goal of these experiments was to measure the scale of the first acoustic peak, which COBE did not have sufficient resolution to resolve.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] This peak corresponds to large scale density variations in the early universe that are created by gravitational instabilities, resulting in acoustical oscillations in the plasma.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The first peak in the anisotropy was tentatively detected by the MAT/TOCO experiment and the result was confirmed by the BOOMERanG and MAXIMA experiments.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] These measurements demonstrated that the geometry of the universe is approximately flat, rather than curved.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] They ruled out cosmic strings as a major component of cosmic structure formation and suggested cosmic inflation was the right theory of structure formation.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Inspired by the initial COBE results of an extremely isotropic and homogeneous background, a series of ground- and balloon-based experiments quantified CMB anisotropies on smaller angular scales over the next decade.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The primary goal of these experiments was to measure the angular scale of the first acoustic peak, for which COBE did not have sufficient resolution.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] These measurements were able to rule out cosmic strings as the leading theory of cosmic structure formation, and suggested cosmic inflation was the right theory.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] During the 1990s, the first peak was measured with increasing sensitivity and by 2000 the BOOMERanG experiment reported that the highest power fluctuations occur at scales of approximately one angular degree.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Together with other cosmological data, these results implied that the geometry of the universe is flat.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] A number of ground-based interferometers provided measurements of the fluctuations with higher accuracy over the next three years, including the Very Small Array, Degree Angular Scale Interferometer (DASI), and the Cosmic Background Imager (CBI).
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] DASI made the first detection of the polarization of the CMB and the CBI provided the first E-mode polarization spectrum with compelling evidence that it is out of phase with the T-mode spectrum.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] In June 2001, NASA launched a second CMB space mission, WMAP, to make much more precise measurements of the large-scale anisotropies over the full sky.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] WMAP used symmetric, rapid-multi-modulated scanning, rapid switching radiometers at five frequencies to minimize non-sky signal noise.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The data from the mission was released in five installments, the last being the nine-year summary.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The results are broadly consistent Lambda CDM models based on 6 free parameters and fitting in to Big Bang cosmology with cosmic inflation.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The Degree Angular Scale Interferometer (DASI) was a telescope installed at the U.S.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] National Science Foundation's Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station in Antarctica.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] It was a 13-element interferometer operating between 26 and 36 GHz (Ka band) in ten bands.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The instrument is similar in design to the Cosmic Background Imager (CBI) and the Very Small Array (VSA).
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] In 2001 The DASI team announced the most detailed measurements of the temperature, or power spectrum of the cosmic microwave background (CMB).
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] These results contained the first detection of the 2nd and 3rd acoustic peaks in the CMB, which were important evidence for inflation theory.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] This announcement was done in conjunction with the BOOMERanG and MAXIMA experiment.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] In 2002 the team reported the first detection of polarization anisotropies in the CMB.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The Atacama Cosmology Telescope (ACT) was a cosmological millimeter-wave telescope located on Cerro Toco in the Atacama Desert in the north of Chile.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] ACT made high-sensitivity, arcminute resolution, microwave-wavelength surveys of the sky in order to study the cosmic microwave background radiation (CMB), the relic radiation left by the Big Bang process.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Located 40 km from San Pedro de Atacama, at an altitude of 5,190 metres (17,030 ft), it was one of the highest ground-based telescopes in the world.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] A third space mission, the ESA (European Space Agency) Planck Surveyor, was launched in May 2009 and performed an even more detailed investigation until it was shut down in October 2013.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Planck employed both HEMT radiometers and bolometer technology and measured the CMB at a smaller scale than WMAP.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Its detectors were trialled in the Antarctic Viper telescope as ACBAR (Arcminute Cosmology Bolometer Array Receiver) experiment—which has produced the most precise measurements at small angular scales to date—and in the Archeops balloon telescope.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] On 21 March 2013, the European-led research team behind the *Planck* cosmology probe released the mission's all-sky map of the cosmic microwave background.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The map suggests the universe is slightly older than researchers expected.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] According to the map, subtle fluctuations in temperature were imprinted on the deep sky when the cosmos was about 370000 years old.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The imprint reflects ripples that arose as early, in the existence of the universe, as the first nonillionth (10−30) of a second.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Apparently, these ripples gave rise to the present vast cosmic web of galaxy clusters and dark matter.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Based on the 2013 data, the universe contains 4.9% ordinary matter, 26.8% dark matter and 68.3% dark energy.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] On 5 February 2015, new data was released by the *Planck* mission, according to which the age of the universe is 13.799±0.021 billion years old and the Hubble constant was measured to be 67.74±0.46 (km/s)/Mpc.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The South Pole Telescope (SPT) is a 10-metre (390 in) diameter telescope located at the Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station, Antarctica.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The telescope is designed for observations in the microwave, millimeter-wave, and submillimeter-wave regions of the electromagnetic spectrum, with the particular design goal of measuring the faint, diffuse emission from the cosmic microwave background (CMB).
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The cosmic microwave background radiation and the cosmological redshift-distance relation are together regarded as the best available evidence for the Big Bang event.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Measurements of the CMB have made the inflationary Big Bang model the Standard Cosmological Model.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The discovery of the CMB in the mid-1960s curtailed interest in alternatives such as the steady state theory.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] In the Big Bang model for the formation of the universe, inflationary cosmology predicts that after about 10−37 seconds the nascent universe underwent exponential growth that smoothed out nearly all irregularities.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The remaining irregularities were caused by quantum fluctuations in the inflaton field that caused the inflation event.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Long before the formation of stars and planets, the early universe was more compact, much hotter and, starting 10−6 seconds after the Big Bang, filled with a uniform glow from its white-hot fog of interacting plasma of photons, electrons, and baryons.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] As the universe expanded, adiabatic cooling caused the energy density of the plasma to decrease until it became favorable for electrons to combine with protons, forming hydrogen atoms.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] This recombination event happened when the temperature was around 3000 K or when the universe was approximately 379,000 years old.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] As photons did not interact with these electrically neutral atoms, the former began to travel freely through space, resulting in the decoupling of matter and radiation.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The color temperature of the ensemble of decoupled photons has continued to diminish ever since; now down to 2.7260±0.0013 K, it will continue to drop as the universe expands.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The intensity of the radiation corresponds to black-body radiation at 2.726 K because red-shifted black-body radiation is just like black-body radiation at a lower temperature.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] According to the Big Bang model, the radiation from the sky we measure today comes from a spherical surface called *the surface of last scattering*.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] This represents the set of locations in space at which the decoupling event is estimated to have occurred and at a point in time such that the photons from that distance have just reached observers.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Most of the radiation energy in the universe is in the cosmic microwave background, making up a fraction of roughly 6×10−5 of the total density of the universe.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Two of the greatest successes of the Big Bang theory are its prediction of the almost perfect black body spectrum and its detailed prediction of the anisotropies in the cosmic microwave background.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The CMB spectrum has become the most precisely measured black body spectrum in nature.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] In the late 1940s Alpher and Herman reasoned that if there was a Big Bang, the expansion of the universe would have stretched the high-energy radiation of the very early universe into the microwave region of the electromagnetic spectrum, and down to a temperature of about 5 K.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] They were slightly off with their estimate, but they had the right idea.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] It took another 15 years for Penzias and Wilson to discover that the microwave background was actually there.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] According to standard cosmology, the CMB gives a snapshot of the hot early universe at the point in time when the temperature dropped enough to allow electrons and protons to form hydrogen atoms.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] This event made the universe nearly transparent to radiation because light was no longer being scattered off free electrons.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] When this occurred some 380,000 years after the Big Bang, the temperature of the universe was about 3,000 K.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] This corresponds to an ambient energy of about 0.26 eV, which is much less than the 13.6 eV ionization energy of hydrogen.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] This epoch is generally known as the "time of last scattering" or the period of recombination or decoupling.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Since decoupling, the color temperature of the background radiation has dropped by an average factor of 1,089 due to the expansion of the universe.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] As the universe expands, the CMB photons are redshifted, causing them to decrease in energy.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The color temperature of this radiation stays inversely proportional to a parameter that describes the relative expansion of the universe over time, known as the scale length.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The high degree of uniformity throughout the observable universe and its faint but measured anisotropy lend strong support for the Big Bang model in general and the ΛCDM ("Lambda Cold Dark Matter") model in particular.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Moreover, the fluctuations are coherent on angular scales that are larger than the apparent cosmological horizon at recombination.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Either such coherence is acausally fine-tuned, or cosmic inflation occurred.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The structure of the cosmic microwave background anisotropies is principally determined by two effects: acoustic oscillations and diffusion damping (also called collisionless damping or Silk damping).
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The acoustic oscillations arise because of a conflict in the photon–baryon plasma in the early universe.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The pressure of the photons tends to erase anisotropies, whereas the gravitational attraction of the baryons, moving at speeds much slower than light, makes them tend to collapse to form overdensities.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] These two effects compete to create acoustic oscillations, which give the microwave background its characteristic peak structure.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The peaks correspond, roughly, to resonances in which the photons decouple when a particular mode is at its peak amplitude.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The peaks contain interesting physical signatures.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The angular scale of the first peak determines the curvature of the universe (but not the topology of the universe).
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The next peak—ratio of the odd peaks to the even peaks—determines the reduced baryon density.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The third peak can be used to get information about the dark-matter density.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The locations of the peaks give important information about the nature of the primordial density perturbations.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] There are two fundamental types of density perturbations called *adiabatic* and *isocurvature*.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] A general density perturbation is a mixture of both, and different theories that purport to explain the primordial density perturbation spectrum predict different mixtures.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] That is, if at one place there is a 1% higher number density of baryons than average, then at that place there is a 1% higher number density of photons (and a 1% higher number density in neutrinos) than average.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] predicts that the primordial perturbations are adiabatic.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] In an isocurvature density perturbation, the sum (over different types of particle) of the fractional additional densities is zero.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] energy in neutrinos than average, would be a pure isocurvature perturbation.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] would produce mostly isocurvature primordial perturbations.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The CMB spectrum can distinguish between these two because these two types of perturbations produce different peak locations.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Isocurvature density perturbations produce a series of peaks whose angular scales (*ℓ* values of the peaks) are roughly in the ratio 1 : 3 : 5 : ..., while adiabatic density perturbations produce peaks whose locations are in the ratio 1 : 2 : 3 : ...
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Observations are consistent with the primordial density perturbations being entirely adiabatic, providing key support for inflation, and ruling out many models of structure formation involving, for example, cosmic strings.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] These effects contribute about equally to the suppression of anisotropies at small scales and give rise to the characteristic exponential damping tail seen in the very small angular scale anisotropies.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The depth of the LSS refers to the fact that the decoupling of the photons and baryons does not happen instantaneously, but instead requires an appreciable fraction of the age of the universe up to that era.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] One method of quantifying how long this process took uses the *photon visibility function* (PVF).
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] This function is defined so that, denoting the PVF by *P*(*t*), the probability that a CMB photon last scattered between time *t* and *t* + *dt* is given by *P*(*t*) *dt*.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The maximum of the PVF (the time when it is most likely that a given CMB photon last scattered) is known quite precisely.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The first-year WMAP results put the time at which *P*(*t*) has a maximum as 372,000 years.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] This is often taken as the "time" at which the CMB formed.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] However, to figure out how *long* it took the photons and baryons to decouple, we need a measure of the width of the PVF.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The WMAP team finds that the PVF is greater than half of its maximal value (the "full width at half maximum", or FWHM) over an interval of 115,000 years.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] By this measure, decoupling took place over roughly 115,000 years, and thus when it was complete, the universe was roughly 487,000 years old.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Since the CMB came into existence, it has apparently been modified by several subsequent physical processes, which are collectively referred to as late-time anisotropy, or secondary anisotropy.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] When the CMB photons became free to travel unimpeded, ordinary matter in the universe was mostly in the form of neutral hydrogen and helium atoms.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] However, observations of galaxies today seem to indicate that most of the volume of the intergalactic medium (IGM) consists of ionized material (since there are few absorption lines due to hydrogen atoms).
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] This implies a period of reionization during which some of the material of the universe was broken into hydrogen ions.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The CMB photons are scattered by free charges such as electrons that are not bound in atoms.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] In an ionized universe, such charged particles have been liberated from neutral atoms by ionizing (ultraviolet) radiation.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Today these free charges are at sufficiently low density in most of the volume of the universe that they do not measurably affect the CMB.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The physics of how photons are scattered by free electrons (Thomson scattering) induces polarization anisotropies on large angular scales.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] This broad angle polarization is correlated with the broad angle temperature perturbation.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Both of these effects have been observed by the WMAP spacecraft, providing evidence that the universe was ionized at very early times, at a redshift around 10.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The detailed provenance of this early ionizing radiation is still a matter of scientific debate.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] It may have included starlight from the very first population of stars (population III stars), supernovae when these first stars reached the end of their lives, or the ionizing radiation produced by the accretion disks of massive black holes.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The time following the emission of the cosmic microwave background—and before the observation of the first stars—is semi-humorously referred to by cosmologists as the Dark Age, and is a period which is under intense study by astronomers (see 21 centimeter radiation).
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The standard cosmology that includes the Big Bang "enjoys considerable popularity among the practicing cosmologists" However, there are challenges to the standard Big Bang framework for explaining CMB data.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] In particular standard cosmology requires fine-tuning of some free parameters, with different values supported by different experimental data.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] As an example of the fine-tuning issue, standard cosmology cannot predict the present temperature of the relic radiation, $T_{0}$ .
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] This value of $T_{0}$ is one of the best results of experimental cosmology and the steady state model can predict it.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] However, alternative models have their own set of problems and they have only made post-facto explanations of existing observations.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Nevertheless, these alternatives have played an important historic role in providing ideas for and challenges to the standard explanation.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The cosmic microwave background is polarized at the level of a few microkelvin.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] There are two types of polarization, called E-mode (or gradient-mode) and B-mode (or curl mode).
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] This is in analogy to electrostatics, in which the electric field (*E*-field) has a vanishing curl and the magnetic field (*B*-field) has a vanishing divergence.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The E-modes arise from Thomson scattering in a heterogeneous plasma.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] E-modes were first seen in 2002 by the Degree Angular Scale Interferometer (DASI).
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] B-modes are expected to be an order of magnitude weaker than the E-modes.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The former are not produced by standard scalar type perturbations, but are generated by gravitational waves during cosmic inflation shortly after the Big Bang.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] However, gravitational lensing of the stronger E-modes can also produce B-mode polarization.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Detecting the original B-modes signal requires analysis of the contamination caused by lensing of the relatively strong E-mode signal.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Models of "slow-roll" cosmic inflation in the early universe predicts primordial gravitational waves that would impact the polarisation of the cosmic microwave background, creating a specific pattern of B-mode polarization.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Detection of this pattern would support the theory of inflation and their strength can confirm and exclude different models of inflation.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The second type of B-modes was discovered in 2013 using the South Pole Telescope with help from the Herschel Space Observatory.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] In October 2014, a measurement of the B-mode polarization at 150 GHz was published by the POLARBEAR experiment.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Compared to BICEP2, POLARBEAR focuses on a smaller patch of the sky and is less susceptible to dust effects.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The team reported that POLARBEAR's measured B-mode polarization was of cosmological origin (and not just due to dust) at a 97.2% confidence level.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The CMB angular anisotropies are usually presented in terms of power per multipole.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The azimuthal variation is not significant and is removed by applying the angular correlation function, giving power spectrum term $C_{\ell }\equiv \langle |a_{\ell m}|^{2}\rangle .$ Increasing values of *ℓ* correspond to higher multipole moments of CMB, meaning more rapid variation with angle.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The monopole term, *ℓ* = 0, is the constant isotropic mean temperature of the CMB, *T**γ* = 2.7255±0.0006 K with one standard deviation confidence.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] This term must be measured with absolute temperature devices, such as the FIRAS instrument on the COBE satellite.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] CMB dipole represents the largest anisotropy, which is in the first spherical harmonic (*ℓ* = 1), a cosine function.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The amplitude of CMB dipole is around 3.3621±0.0010 mK.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The CMB dipole moment is interpreted as the peculiar motion of the Earth relative to the CMB.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Its amplitude depends on the time due to the Earth's orbit about the barycenter of the solar system.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] This enables us to add a time-dependent term to the dipole expression.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The modulation of this term is 1 year, which fits the observation done by COBE FIRAS.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The dipole moment does not encode any primordial information.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] From the CMB data, it is seen that the Sun appears to be moving at 369.82±0.11 km/s relative to the reference frame of the CMB (also called the CMB rest frame, or the frame of reference in which there is no motion through the CMB).
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The Local Group — the galaxy group that includes our own Milky Way galaxy — appears to be moving at 620±15 km/s in the direction of galactic longitude *ℓ* = 271.9°±2°, *b* = 30°±3°.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The dipole is now used to calibrate mapping studies.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The temperature variation in the CMB temperature maps at higher multipoles, or *ℓ* ≥ 2, is considered to be the result of perturbations of the density in the early Universe, before the recombination epoch at a redshift of around *z* ⋍ 1100.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Before recombination, the Universe consisted of a hot, dense plasma of electrons and baryons.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] In such a hot dense environment, electrons and protons could not form any neutral atoms.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The baryons in such early Universe remained highly ionized and so were tightly coupled with photons through the effect of Thompson scattering.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] These phenomena caused the pressure and gravitational effects to act against each other, and triggered fluctuations in the photon-baryon plasma.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Quickly after the recombination epoch, the rapid expansion of the universe caused the plasma to cool down and these fluctuations are "frozen into" the CMB maps we observe today.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] With the increasingly precise data provided by WMAP, there have been a number of claims that the CMB exhibits anomalies, such as very large scale anisotropies, anomalous alignments, and non-Gaussian distributions.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The most longstanding of these is the low-*ℓ* multipole controversy.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Even in the COBE map, it was observed that the quadrupole (*ℓ* = 2, spherical harmonic) has a low amplitude compared to the predictions of the Big Bang.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] In particular, the quadrupole and octupole (*ℓ* = 3) modes appear to have an unexplained alignment with each other and with both the ecliptic plane and equinoxes.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] A number of groups have suggested that this could be the signature of quantum corrections or new physics at the greatest observable scales; other groups suspect systematic errors in the data.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Ultimately, due to the foregrounds and the cosmic variance problem, the greatest modes will never be as well measured as the small angular scale modes.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] The analyses were performed on two maps that have had the foregrounds removed as far as possible: the "internal linear combination" map of the WMAP collaboration and a similar map prepared by Max Tegmark and others.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Later analyses have pointed out that these are the modes most susceptible to foreground contamination from synchrotron, dust, and bremsstrahlung emission, and from experimental uncertainty in the monopole and dipole.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] A full Bayesian analysis of the WMAP power spectrum demonstrates that the quadrupole prediction of Lambda-CDM cosmology is consistent with the data at the 10% level and that the observed octupole is not remarkable.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Carefully accounting for the procedure used to remove the foregrounds from the full sky map further reduces the significance of the alignment by ~5%.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Recent observations with the Planck telescope, which is very much more sensitive than WMAP and has a larger angular resolution, record the same anomaly, and so instrumental error (but not foreground contamination) appears to be ruled out.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Coincidence is a possible explanation, chief scientist from WMAP, Charles L.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] Measurements of the density of quasars based on Wide-field Infrared Survey Explorer data finds a dipole significantly different from the one extracted from the CMB anisotropy.
[src:cosmology/cosmic-microwave-background] This difference is in conflict with the cosmological principle.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] In the science of astronomy, physical cosmology is concerned with the study of the chronology of the universe, the observable universe's origin, its large-scale structures and dynamics, and the ultimate fate of the universe, including the physical laws that govern these areas.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Physical cosmology is a sub-branch of astronomy that is concerned with the universe as a whole.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Modern physical cosmology is dominated by the Big Bang Theory which attempts to bring together observational astronomy and particle physics; more specifically, a standard parameterization of the Big Bang with dark matter and dark energy, known as the Lambda-CDM model.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Spergel has described cosmology as a "historical science" because "when we look out in space, we look back in time" due to the finite nature of the speed of light.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Physics and astrophysics have played central roles in shaping our understanding of the universe through scientific observation and experiment.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Physical cosmology was shaped through both mathematics and observation in an analysis of the whole universe.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] The universe is generally understood to have begun with the Big Bang, followed almost instantaneously by cosmic inflation, an expansion of space from which the universe is thought to have emerged 13.799 ± 0.021 billion years ago.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Cosmogony studies the origin of the universe, and cosmography maps the features of the universe.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] In Diderot's *Encyclopédie*, cosmology is broken down into uranology (the science of the heavens), aerology (the science of the air), geology (the science of the continents), and hydrology (the science of waters).
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Metaphysical cosmology has also been described as the placing of humans in the universe in relationship to all other entities.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Physical cosmology is the branch of physics and astrophysics that deals with the study of the physical origins and evolution of the universe.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] It also includes the study of the nature of the universe on a large scale.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] In its earliest form, it was what is now known as "celestial mechanics," the study of the heavens.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Greek philosophers Aristarchus of Samos, Aristotle, and Ptolemy proposed different cosmological theories.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] The geocentric Ptolemaic system was the prevailing theory until the 16th century when Nicolaus Copernicus, and subsequently Johannes Kepler and Galileo Galilei, proposed a heliocentric system.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] This is one of the most famous examples of epistemological rupture in physical cosmology.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Isaac Newton's *Principia Mathematica*, published in 1687, was the first description of the law of universal gravitation.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] It provided a physical mechanism for Kepler's laws and also allowed the anomalies in previous systems, caused by gravitational interaction between the planets, to be resolved.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] A fundamental difference between Newton's cosmology and those preceding it was the Copernican principle—that the bodies on Earth obey the same physical laws as all celestial bodies.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] This was a crucial philosophical advance in physical cosmology.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] In the 19th century various cosmological paradoxes appeared related to Newtonian gravity, including Olbers' paradox (why is the sky dark?), Bentley–Seeliger paradox (why gravitation does not make the universe collapse?) and the heat death paradox (why hasn't the universe reach thermal equilibrium?).
[src:cosmology/cosmology] All three indicated a non-infinite universe.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] General relativity prompted cosmogonists such as Willem de Sitter, Karl Schwarzschild, and Arthur Eddington to explore its astronomical ramifications, which enhanced the ability of astronomers to study very distant objects.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Physicists began changing the assumption that the universe was static and unchanging.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] In 1922, Alexander Friedmann introduced the idea of an expanding universe that contained moving matter.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] While Heber Curtis argued for the idea that spiral nebulae were star systems in their own right as island universes, Mount Wilson astronomer Harlow Shapley championed the model of a cosmos made up of the Milky Way star system only.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] This difference of ideas came to a climax with the organization of the Great Debate on 26 April 1920 at the meeting of the U.S.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] National Academy of Sciences in Washington, D.C.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] The debate was resolved when Edwin Hubble detected Cepheid Variables in the Andromeda Galaxy in 1923 and 1924.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Their distance established spiral nebulae well beyond the edge of the Milky Way.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Subsequent modelling of the universe explored the possibility that the cosmological constant, introduced by Einstein in his 1917 paper, may result in an expanding universe, depending on its value.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Thus the Big Bang model was proposed by the Belgian priest Georges Lemaître in 1927 which was subsequently corroborated by Edwin Hubble's discovery of the redshift in 1929 and later by the discovery of the cosmic microwave background radiation by Arno Penzias and Robert Woodrow Wilson in 1964.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] These findings were a first step to rule out some of many alternative cosmologies.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Since around 1990, several dramatic advances in observational cosmology have transformed cosmology from a largely speculative science into a predictive science with precise agreement between theory and observation.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] These advances include observations of the microwave background from the COBE, WMAP and Planck satellites, large new galaxy redshift surveys including 2dfGRS and SDSS, and observations of distant supernovae and gravitational lensing.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] These observations matched the predictions of the cosmic inflation theory, a modified Big Bang theory, and the specific version known as the Lambda-CDM model.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] This has led many to refer to modern times as the "golden age of cosmology".
[src:cosmology/cosmology] In 2014, the BICEP2 collaboration claimed that they had detected the imprint of gravitational waves in the cosmic microwave background.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] However, this result was later found to be spurious: the supposed evidence of gravitational waves was in fact due to interstellar dust.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] On 1 December 2014, at the *Planck 2014* meeting in Ferrara, Italy, astronomers reported that the universe is 13.8 billion years old and composed of 4.9% atomic matter, 26.6% dark matter and 68.5% dark energy.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Religious or mythological cosmology is a body of beliefs based on mythological, religious, and esoteric literature and traditions of creation and eschatology.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Historically, religious cosmology and myths have intertwined with scientific and philosophical understandings, but recent scientific cosmology has challenged many aspects of religious cosmology.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Generally, scientific cosmology is grounded in empirical evidence and observations, while religious and mythological cosmology relies on the persuasive arguments by prophets, philosophers, or mathematicians.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Cosmology deals with the world as the totality of space, time and all phenomena.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Historically, it has had quite a broad scope, and in many cases was found in religion.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Some questions about the Universe are beyond the scope of scientific inquiry but may still be interrogated through appeals to other philosophical approaches like dialectics.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Charles Kahn, a historian of philosophy, attributed the origins of ancient Greek cosmology to Anaximander.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Table notes: the term "static" simply means not expanding and not contracting.
[src:cosmology/cosmology] Symbol *G* represents Newton's gravitational constant; Λ (Lambda) is the cosmological constant.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] In physical cosmology and astronomy, **dark energy** is a proposed form of energy that affects the universe on its largest scales.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Its primary effect is to drive the accelerating expansion of the universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] It also slows the rate of structure formation.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Dark energy's density is very low: 7×10−30 g/cm3 (6×10−10 J/m3 in mass-energy), much lower than the density of ordinary matter or dark matter within galaxies.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] However, it dominates the universe's mass–energy content because it is uniform across space.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The first observational evidence for dark energy's existence came from measurements of supernovae.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Type Ia supernovae have constant luminosity, which means they can be used to accurately measure distances.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Comparing this distance to the redshift (which measures the speed at which the supernova is receding) shows that the universe's expansion is accelerating.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Prior to this observation, scientists thought that the gravitational attraction of matter and energy in the universe would cause the universe's expansion to slow over time.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Since the discovery of accelerating expansion, several independent lines of evidence have been discovered that support the existence of dark energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The exact nature of dark energy remains a mystery, and many possible explanations have been theorized.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The main candidates are a cosmological constant (representing a constant energy density filling space homogeneously) and scalar fields (dynamic quantities having energy densities that vary in time and space) such as quintessence or moduli.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] A cosmological constant would remain constant across time and space, while scalar fields can vary.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Yet other possibilities are interacting dark energy (see the section *Dark energy § Theories of dark energy*), an observational effect, cosmological coupling, and shockwave cosmology (see the section *§ Alternatives to dark energy*).
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The "cosmological constant" is the simplest candidate for dark energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] It is a constant term that can be added to the Einstein field equations of general relativity.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] If considered as a "source term" in the field equation, it can be viewed as equivalent to the mass of empty space (which conceptually could be either positive or negative), or "vacuum energy".
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The cosmological constant was first proposed by Einstein as a mechanism to obtain a solution to the gravitational field equation that would lead to a static universe, effectively using dark energy to balance gravity.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Einstein gave the cosmological constant the symbol Λ (capital lambda).
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Einstein stated that the cosmological constant required that 'empty space takes the role of gravitating negative masses that are distributed all over the interstellar space'.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The mechanism was an example of fine-tuning, and it was later realized that Einstein's static universe would not be stable: local inhomogeneities would ultimately lead to either the runaway expansion or contraction of the universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The equilibrium is unstable: if the universe expands slightly, then the expansion releases vacuum energy, which causes yet more expansion.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Likewise, a universe that contracts slightly will continue contracting.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] According to Einstein, "empty space" can possess its own energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Because this energy is a property of space itself, it would not be diluted as space expands.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] As more space comes into existence, more of this energy-of-space would appear, thereby causing accelerated expansion.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] These sorts of disturbances are inevitable, due to the uneven distribution of matter throughout the universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Further, observations made by Edwin Hubble in 1929 showed that the universe appears to be expanding and is not static.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Einstein reportedly referred to his failure to predict the idea of a dynamic universe, in contrast to a static universe, as his greatest blunder.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Alan Guth and Alexei Starobinsky proposed in 1980 that a negative pressure field, similar in concept to dark energy, could drive cosmic inflation in the very early universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Inflation postulates that some repulsive force, qualitatively similar to dark energy, resulted in an enormous and exponential expansion of the universe during its earliest stages.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Such expansion is an essential feature of most current models of the Big Bang.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] However, inflation must have occurred at a much higher energy density than the dark energy we observe today, and inflation is thought to have completely ended when the universe was just a fraction of a second old.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] It is unclear what relation, if any, exists between dark energy and inflation.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Even after inflationary models became accepted, the cosmological constant was thought to be irrelevant to the current universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Nearly all inflation models predict that the total (matter+energy) density of the universe should be very close to the critical density.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] During the 1980s, most cosmological research focused on models with critical density in matter only, usually 95% cold dark matter (CDM) and 5% ordinary matter (baryons).
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] These difficulties became stronger after the discovery of anisotropy in the cosmic microwave background by the COBE spacecraft in 1992, and several modified CDM models came under active study through the mid-1990s: these included the Lambda-CDM model and a mixed cold/hot dark matter model.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The first direct evidence for dark energy came from supernova observations in 1998 of accelerated expansion in Riess *et al.* and in Perlmutter *et al.*, and the Lambda-CDM model then became the leading model.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Soon after, dark energy was supported by independent observations: in 2000, the BOOMERanG and Maxima cosmic microwave background experiments observed the first acoustic peak in the cosmic microwave background, showing that the total (matter+energy) density is close to 100% of critical density.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Then in 2001, the 2dF Galaxy Redshift Survey gave strong evidence that the matter density is around 30% of critical.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The large difference between these two supports a smooth component of dark energy making up the difference.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Much more precise measurements from WMAP in 2003–2010 have continued to support the standard model and give more accurate measurements of the key parameters.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The term "dark energy" was coined by cosmologist Michael S.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Turner in 1998 for a paper written with Saul Perlmutter and Martin White.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The nature of dark energy is more hypothetical than that of dark matter, and many things about it remain in the realm of speculation.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Dark energy is thought to be very homogeneous and not dense, and is not known to interact through any of the fundamental forces other than gravity.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Since it is rarefied and un-massive—roughly 10−27 kg/m3—it is unlikely to be detectable in laboratory experiments.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The reason dark energy can have such a profound effect on the universe, making up 68% of universal density in spite of being so dilute, is that it is believed to uniformly fill otherwise empty space.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The vacuum energy, that is, the particle–antiparticle pairs generated and mutually annihilated within a time frame in accord with Heisenberg's uncertainty principle in the energy–time formulation, has been often invoked as the main contribution to dark energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The mass–energy equivalence postulated by general relativity implies that the vacuum energy should exert a gravitational force.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Hence, the vacuum energy is expected to contribute to the cosmological constant, which in turn impinges on the accelerated expansion of the universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] However, the cosmological constant problem asserts that there is a huge disagreement between the observed values of vacuum energy density and the theoretical large value of zero-point energy obtained by quantum field theory; the problem remains unresolved.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Independently of its actual nature, dark energy would need to have a strong negative pressure to explain the observed acceleration of the expansion of the universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] According to general relativity, the pressure within a substance contributes to its gravitational attraction for other objects just as its mass density does.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] This happens because the physical quantity that causes matter to generate gravitational effects is the stress–energy tensor, which contains both the energy (or matter) density of a substance and its pressure.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] In the Friedmann–Lemaître–Robertson–Walker metric, it can be shown that a strong constant negative pressure (*i.e.,* tension) in all the universe causes an acceleration in the expansion if the universe is already expanding, or a deceleration in contraction if the universe is already contracting.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] This accelerating expansion effect is sometimes labeled "gravitational repulsion".
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] In standard cosmology, there are three components of the universe: matter, radiation, and dark energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Matter is anything whose energy density scales with the inverse cube of the scale factor, i.e., *ρ* ∝ *a*−3, while radiation is anything whose energy density scales to the inverse fourth power of the scale factor (*ρ* ∝ *a*−4).
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] This can be understood intuitively: for an ordinary particle in a cube-shaped box, doubling the length of an edge of the box decreases the density (and hence energy density) by a factor of eight (23).
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] For radiation, the decrease in energy density is greater, because an increase in spatial distance also causes a redshift and hence a decrease in energy (c.f. the Planck relation).
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The final component is dark energy: it is an intrinsic property of space and has a constant energy density, regardless of the dimensions of the volume under consideration (*ρ* ∝ *a*0).
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Thus, unlike ordinary matter, it is not diluted by the expansion of space.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] High-precision measurements of the expansion of the universe are required to understand how the expansion rate changes over time and space.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] In general relativity, the evolution of the expansion rate is estimated from the curvature of the universe and the cosmological equation of state (the relationship between temperature, pressure, and combined matter, energy, and vacuum energy density for any region of space).
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Measuring the equation of state for dark energy is one of the biggest efforts in observational cosmology today.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Adding the cosmological constant to cosmology's standard FLRW metric leads to the Lambda-CDM model, which has been referred to as the "*standard model of cosmology*" because of its precise agreement with observations.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] As of 2013, the Lambda-CDM model is consistent with a series of increasingly rigorous cosmological observations, including the Planck spacecraft and the Supernova Legacy Survey (SNLS).
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] First results from the SNLS reveal that the average behavior (i.e., equation of state) of dark energy behaves like Einstein's cosmological constant to a precision of 10%.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Recent results from the Hubble Space Telescope Higher-Z Team indicate that dark energy has been present for at least 9 billion years and during the period preceding cosmic acceleration.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Results suggest that the density of dark energy is slowly decreasing with time.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] In 1998, the High-Z Supernova Search Team published observations of Type Ia ("one-A") supernovae.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] In 1999, the Supernova Cosmology Project followed by suggesting that the expansion of the universe is accelerating.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The 2011 Nobel Prize in Physics was awarded to Saul Perlmutter, Brian P.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Riess for their leadership in the discovery.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Since then, these observations have been corroborated by several independent sources.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Measurements of the cosmic microwave background, gravitational lensing, and the large-scale structure of the cosmos, as well as improved measurements of supernovae, have been consistent with the Lambda-CDM model.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Some people argue that the only indications for the existence of dark energy are observations of distance measurements and their associated redshifts.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Cosmic microwave background anisotropies and baryon acoustic oscillations serve only to demonstrate that distances to a given redshift are larger than would be expected from a "dusty" Friedmann–Lemaître universe and the local measured Hubble constant.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Supernovae are useful for cosmology because they are excellent standard candles across cosmological distances.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] They allow researchers to measure the expansion history of the universe by looking at the relationship between the distance to an object and its redshift, which gives how fast it is receding from us.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The relationship is roughly linear, according to Hubble's law.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] It is relatively easy to measure redshift, but finding the distance to an object is more difficult.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Usually, astronomers use standard candles: objects for which the intrinsic brightness, or absolute magnitude, is known.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] This allows the object's distance to be measured from its actual observed brightness, or apparent magnitude.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Type Ia supernovae are the most accurate known standard candles across cosmological distances because of their extreme and consistent luminosity.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Recent observations of supernovae are consistent with a universe made up 66.6% of dark energy and 33.4% of a combination of dark matter and baryonic matter assuming a flat Lambda-CDM model.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The theory of large-scale structure, which governs the formation of structures in the universe (stars, quasars, galaxies and galaxy groups and clusters), also suggests that the density of matter in the universe is only 30% of the critical density.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] A 2011 survey, the WiggleZ galaxy survey of more than 200,000 galaxies, provided further evidence towards the existence of dark energy, although the exact physics behind it remains unknown.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The WiggleZ survey from the Australian Astronomical Observatory scanned the galaxies to determine their redshift.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The data confirmed cosmic acceleration up to half of the age of the universe (7 billion years) and constrain its inhomogeneity to 1 part in 10.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] This provides a confirmation to cosmic acceleration independent of supernovae.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The existence of dark energy, in whatever form, is needed to reconcile the measured geometry of space with the total amount of matter in the universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Measurements of cosmic microwave background anisotropies indicate that the universe is close to flat.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] For the shape of the universe to be flat, the mass–energy density of the universe must be equal to the critical density.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The total amount of matter in the universe (including baryons and dark matter), as measured from the cosmic microwave background spectrum, accounts for only about 30% of the critical density.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] This implies the existence of an additional form of energy to account for the remaining 70%.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The Wilkinson Microwave Anisotropy Probe (WMAP) spacecraft seven-year analysis estimated a universe made up of 72.8% dark energy, 22.7% dark matter, and 4.5% ordinary matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Work done in 2013 based on the Planck spacecraft observations of the cosmic microwave background gave a more accurate estimate of 68.3% dark energy, 26.8% dark matter, and 4.9% ordinary matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Accelerated cosmic expansion causes gravitational potential wells and hills to flatten as photons pass through them, producing cold spots and hot spots on the cosmic microwave background aligned with vast supervoids and superclusters.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] This so-called late-time Integrated Sachs–Wolfe effect (ISW) is a direct signal of dark energy in a flat universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] A new approach to test evidence of dark energy through observational Hubble constant data (OHD), also known as cosmic chronometers, has gained significant attention in recent years.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The Hubble constant, *H*(*z*), is measured as a function of cosmological redshift.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] OHD directly tracks the expansion history of the universe by taking passively evolving early-type galaxies as "cosmic chronometers".
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] From this point, this approach provides standard clocks in the universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The core of this idea is the measurement of the differential age evolution as a function of redshift of these cosmic chronometers.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The reliance on a differential quantity, ⁠Δ*z*/Δ*t*⁠, brings more information and is appealing for computation: It can minimize many common issues and systematic effects.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Analyses of supernovae and baryon acoustic oscillations (BAO) are based on integrals of the Hubble parameter, whereas ⁠Δ*z*/Δ*t*⁠ measures it directly.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] For these reasons, this method has been widely used to examine the accelerated cosmic expansion and study properties of dark energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Dark energy's status as a hypothetical force with unknown properties makes it an active target of research.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The problem is attacked from a variety of angles, such as modifying the prevailing theory of gravity (general relativity), attempting to pin down the properties of dark energy, and finding alternative ways to explain the observational data.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The simplest explanation for dark energy is that it is an intrinsic, fundamental energy of space.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] This is the cosmological constant, usually represented by the Greek letter Λ (Lambda, hence the name Lambda-CDM model).
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Since energy and mass are related according to the equation *E* = *mc*2, Einstein's theory of general relativity predicts that this energy will have a gravitational effect.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] It is sometimes called *vacuum energy* because it is the energy density of empty space – of vacuum.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] A major outstanding problem is that the same quantum field theories predict a huge cosmological constant, about 120 orders of magnitude too large.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] This would need to be almost, but not exactly, cancelled by an equally large term of the opposite sign.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Some supersymmetric theories require a cosmological constant that is exactly zero.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] It is also unknown whether a positive cosmological constant is consistent with simple interpretations of string theory, in which our universe is a false vacuum with a positive cosmological constant.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] It has been conjectured by Ulf Danielsson *et al.* that no such state exists.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] However, even if string theory does not allow such a false vacuum, other models of dark energy, such as quintessence, could still be viable.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] In quintessence models of dark energy, the observed acceleration of the scale factor is caused by the potential energy of a dynamical field, referred to as quintessence field.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Quintessence differs from the cosmological constant in that it can vary in space and time.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] In order for it not to clump and form structure like matter, the field must be very light so that it has a large Compton wavelength.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] In the simplest scenarios, the quintessence field has a canonical kinetic term, is minimally coupled to gravity, and does not feature higher order operations in its Lagrangian.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] No evidence of quintessence is yet available, nor has it been ruled out.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] It generally predicts a slightly slower acceleration of the expansion of the universe than the cosmological constant.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Some scientists think that the best evidence for quintessence would come from violations of Einstein's equivalence principle and variation of the fundamental constants in space or time.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The coincidence problem asks why the acceleration of the Universe began when it did.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] If acceleration began earlier in the universe, structures such as galaxies would never have had time to form, and life, at least as we know it, would never have had a chance to exist.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Proponents of the anthropic principle view this as support for their arguments.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] However, many models of quintessence have a so-called "tracker" behavior, which solves this problem.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] In these models, the quintessence field has a density which closely tracks (but is less than) the radiation density until matter–radiation equality, which triggers quintessence to start behaving as dark energy, eventually dominating the universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] This naturally sets the low energy scale of the dark energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] In 2004, when scientists fit the evolution of dark energy with the cosmological data, they found that the equation of state $\omega$ had possibly crossed the cosmological constant boundary $\omega =-1$ from above to below.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] A no-go theorem has been proved that this scenario requires models with at least two types of scalar fields.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] This scenario is called Quintom, which was proposed by Xinmin Zhang's group in 2004.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Some special cases of quintessence are phantom dark energy, in which the energy density of quintessence actually increases with time, and k-essence (short for kinetic quintessence) which has a non-standard form of kinetic energy such as a negative kinetic energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] They can have unusual properties: phantom dark energy, for example, can cause a Big Rip.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] A group of researchers argued in 2021 that observations of the Hubble tension may imply that only quintessence models with a nonzero coupling constant are viable.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] This class of theories attempts to come up with an all-encompassing theory of both dark matter and dark energy as a single phenomenon that modifies the laws of gravity at various scales.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] This could, for example, treat dark energy and dark matter as different facets of the same unknown substance, or postulate that cold dark matter decays into dark energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Another class of theories that unifies dark matter and dark energy are suggested to be covariant theories of modified gravities.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] These theories alter the dynamics of spacetime such that the modified dynamics stems to what have been assigned to the presence of dark energy and dark matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Dark energy could in principle interact not only with the rest of the dark sector, but also with ordinary matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] However, cosmology alone is not sufficient to effectively constrain the strength of the coupling between dark energy and baryons, so that other indirect techniques or laboratory searches have to be adopted.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] It was briefly theorized in the early 2020s that excess observed in the XENON1T detector in Italy may have been caused by a chameleon model of dark energy, but further experiments disproved this possibility.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The density of dark energy might have varied in time during the history of the universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Modern observational data allows us to estimate the present density of dark energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Using baryon acoustic oscillations, it is possible to investigate the effect of dark energy in the history of the universe, and constrain parameters of the equation of state of dark energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] To that end, several models have been proposed.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] One of the most popular models is the Chevallier–Polarski–Linder model (CPL).
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Some other common models are Barboza & Alcaniz (2008), Jassal et al.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] There is some observational evidence that dark energy is indeed decreasing with time.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Data from the Dark Energy Spectroscopic Instrument (DESI), tracking the size of baryon acoustic oscillations over the universe's expansion history, suggests that the amount of dark energy is 10% lower than it was 4.5 billion years ago.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] However, there is not yet sufficient data to rule out dark energy being the cosmological constant.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The evidence for dark energy is heavily dependent on the theory of general relativity.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Therefore, it is conceivable that a modification to general relativity also eliminates the need for dark energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] There are many such theories, and research is ongoing.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The measurement of the speed of gravity in the first gravitational wave measured by non-gravitational means (GW170817) ruled out many modified gravity theories as explanations to dark energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Some alternatives to dark energy, such as inhomogeneous cosmology, aim to explain the observational data by a more refined use of established theories.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] In this scenario, dark energy does not actually exist, and is merely a measurement artifact.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] For example, if we are located in an emptier-than-average region of space, the observed cosmic expansion rate could be mistaken for a variation in time, or acceleration.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] A different approach uses a cosmological extension of the equivalence principle to show how space might appear to be expanding more rapidly in the voids surrounding our local cluster.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] While weak, such effects considered cumulatively over billions of years could become significant, creating the illusion of cosmic acceleration, and making it appear as if we live in a Hubble bubble.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Yet other possibilities are that the accelerated expansion of the universe is an illusion caused by the relative motion of us to the rest of the universe, or that the statistical methods employed were flawed.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] A laboratory direct detection attempt failed to detect any force associated with dark energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Observational skepticism explanations of dark energy have generally not gained much traction among cosmologists.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] For example, a paper that suggested the anisotropy of the local Universe has been misrepresented as dark energy was quickly countered by another paper claiming errors in the original paper.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Another study questioning the essential assumption that the luminosity of Type Ia supernovae does not vary with stellar population age was also swiftly rebutted by other cosmologists.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Another theory called "cosmological coupling" has been proposed as an explanation of dark energy effects.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The idea is to require the local description of black holes, the Kerr metric, to match the description of the overall universe assumed in modern cosmology, Friedmann-Robertson-Walker metric, rather than spatially flat spacetime at infinity.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Then one finds that black holes gain mass as the universe expands.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The rate is measured to increase proportionally to *a*3 , where a is some scale factor for matter in the universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] This particular rate means that the energy density of black holes remains constant over time, mimicking dark energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Other astrophysicists are skeptical, with a variety of papers claiming that the theory fails to explain other observations.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Still other work suggests observations cannot rule out this model, but some theoretical work claims it can be ruled out.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Shockwave cosmology, proposed by Joel Smoller and Blake Temple in 2003, has the "big bang" as an explosion inside a black hole, producing the expanding volume of space and matter that includes the observable universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] A related theory by Smoller, Temple, and Vogler proposes that this shockwave may have resulted in our part of the universe having a lower density than that surrounding it, causing the accelerated expansion normally attributed to dark energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] They also propose that this related theory could be tested: a universe with dark energy should give a figure for the cubic correction to redshift versus luminosity C = −0.180 at a = a whereas for Smoller, Temple, and Vogler's alternative C should be positive rather than negative.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] They give a more precise calculation for their shockwave model alternative as: the cubic correction to redshift versus luminosity at a = a is C = 0.359.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Although shockwave cosmology produces a universe that "looks essentially identical to the aftermath of the big bang", cosmologists consider that it needs further development before it could be seen as a more advantageous model than the big bang theory (or standard model) in explaining the universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] In particular, and especially for the proposed alternative to dark energy, it would need to explain big bang nucleosynthesis, the quantitative details of the microwave background anisotropies, the Lyman-alpha forest, and galaxy surveys.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Cosmologists estimate that the acceleration began roughly 5 billion years ago.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Before that, it is thought that the expansion was decelerating, due to the attractive influence of matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The density of dark matter in an expanding universe decreases more quickly than dark energy, and eventually the dark energy dominates.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Specifically, when the volume of the universe doubles, the density of dark matter is halved, but the density of dark energy is nearly unchanged (it is exactly constant in the case of a cosmological constant).
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Projections into the future can differ radically for different models of dark energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] For a cosmological constant, or any other model that predicts that the acceleration will continue indefinitely, the ultimate result will be that galaxies outside the Local Group will have a line-of-sight velocity that continually increases with time, eventually far exceeding the speed of light.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Because the Hubble parameter is decreasing with time, there can actually be cases where a galaxy that is receding from us faster than light does manage to emit a signal which reaches us eventually.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] As galaxies approach the point of crossing this cosmological event horizon, the light from them will become more and more redshifted, to the point where the wavelength becomes too large to detect in practice and the galaxies appear to vanish completely (*see* Future of an expanding universe).
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Planet Earth, the Milky Way, and the Local Group of galaxies of which the Milky Way is a part, would all remain virtually undisturbed as the rest of the universe recedes and disappears from view.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] In this scenario, the Local Group would ultimately suffer heat death, just as was hypothesized for the flat, matter-dominated universe before measurements of cosmic acceleration.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] There are other, more speculative ideas about the future of the universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The phantom dark energy model of dark energy results in *divergent* expansion, which would imply that the effective force of dark energy continues growing until it dominates all other forces in the universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] Under this scenario, dark energy would ultimately tear apart all gravitationally bound structures, including galaxies and solar systems, and eventually overcome the electrical and nuclear forces to tear apart atoms themselves, ending the universe in a "Big Rip".
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] On the other hand, dark energy might dissipate with time or even become attractive.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] While none of these are supported by observations, they are not ruled out.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] The astrophysicist David Merritt identifies dark energy as an example of an "auxiliary hypothesis", an ad hoc postulate that is added to a theory in response to observations that falsify it.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] He argues that the dark energy hypothesis is a conventionalist hypothesis, that is, a hypothesis that adds no empirical content and hence is unfalsifiable in the sense defined by Karl Popper.
[src:cosmology/dark-energy] However, his opinion is not shared by all scientists.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] In astronomy and cosmology, **dark matter** is an invisible and hypothetical form of matter that does not interact with electromagnetic radiation, including light.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Dark matter is implied by gravitational effects that cannot be explained by general relativity unless more matter is present than can be observed.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Such effects occur in the context of formation and evolution of galaxies, gravitational lensing, the observable universe's current structure, mass position in galactic collisions, the motion of galaxies within galaxy clusters, and cosmic microwave background anisotropies.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Dark matter is thought to serve as gravitational scaffolding for cosmic structures.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] After the Big Bang, dark matter clumped into blobs along narrow filaments with superclusters of galaxies forming a cosmic web at scales on which entire galaxies appear like tiny particles.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] In the standard Lambda-CDM model of cosmology, the mass–energy content of the universe is 5% ordinary matter, 26.8% dark matter, and 68.2% a form of energy known as dark energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Thus, dark matter constitutes 85% of the total mass, while dark energy and dark matter constitute 95% of the total mass–energy content.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] While the density of dark matter is significant in the halo around a galaxy, its local density in the Solar System is much less than normal matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The total of all the dark matter out to the orbit of Neptune would add up to about 1017 kg, the same as a large asteroid.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Dark matter is classified as "cold", "warm", or "hot" according to velocity (more precisely, its free streaming length).
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Recent models have favored a cold dark matter scenario, in which structures emerge by the gradual accumulation of particles.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Dark matter is not known to interact with ordinary baryonic matter and radiation except through gravity, making it difficult to detect in the laboratory.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The most prevalent explanation is that dark matter is some as-yet-undiscovered subatomic particle, such as either weakly interacting massive particles (WIMPs) or axions.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The other main possibility is that dark matter is composed of primordial black holes.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Although the astrophysics community generally accepts the existence of dark matter, a minority of astrophysicists, intrigued by specific observations that are not well explained by ordinary dark matter, argue for various modifications of the standard laws of general relativity.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] These include modified Newtonian dynamics (MOND), tensor–vector–scalar gravity, and entropic gravity.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] So far, none of the proposed modified gravity theories can describe every piece of observational evidence at the same time, suggesting that even if gravity has to be modified, some form of dark matter would still be required.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The hypothesis of dark matter has an elaborate history.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Lord Kelvin discussed the potential number of stars around the Sun in the appendices of a book based on a series of lectures given in 1884 in Baltimore.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] He inferred their density using the observed velocity dispersion of the stars near the Sun, assuming that the Sun was 20–100 million years old.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] He posed what would happen if there were a thousand million stars within 1 kiloparsec of the Sun (at which distance their parallax would be 1 milli-arcsecond).
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] In 1906, Henri Poincaré used the French term [*matière obscure*] ("dark matter") in discussing Kelvin's work.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] He concluded that the amount of dark matter would need to be less than that of visible matter, which was later found to be false.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The second to suggest the existence of dark matter using stellar velocities was Dutch astronomer Jacobus Kapteyn in 1922.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] A publication from 1930 by Swedish astronomer Knut Lundmark points to him being the first to hypothesize that the universe must contain much more mass than can be observed.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Dutch radio astronomy pioneer Jan Oort also hypothesized the existence of dark matter in 1932.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Oort was studying stellar motions in the galactic neighborhood and found the mass in the galactic plane must be greater than what was observed, but this measurement was later determined to be incorrect.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] In 1933, Swiss astrophysicist Fritz Zwicky studied galaxy clusters while working at Caltech and made a similar inference.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Zwicky applied the virial theorem to the Coma Cluster and obtained evidence of unseen mass he called *dunkle Materie* ('dark matter').
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Zwicky estimated its mass based on the motions of galaxies near its edge and compared that to an estimate based on its brightness and number of galaxies.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] He estimated the cluster had about 400 times more mass than was visually observable.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The gravity effect of the visible galaxies was far too small for such fast orbits, thus mass must be hidden from view.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Based on these conclusions, Zwicky inferred some unseen matter provided the mass and associated gravitational attraction to hold the cluster together.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Zwicky's estimates were off by more than an order of magnitude, mainly due to an obsolete value of the Hubble constant; the same calculation today shows a smaller fraction, using greater values for luminous mass.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Nonetheless, Zwicky did correctly conclude from his calculation that most of the gravitational matter present was dark.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] However, unlike modern theories, Zwicky considered "dark matter" to be non-luminous ordinary matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Further indications of mass-to-light ratio anomalies came from measurements of galaxy rotation curves.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Babcock reported the rotation curve for the Andromeda Galaxy (then called the Andromeda Nebula), which suggested the mass-to-luminosity ratio increases radially.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] He attributed it to either light absorption within the galaxy or modified dynamics in the outer portions of the spiral, rather than to unseen matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Following Babcock's 1939 report of unexpectedly rapid rotation in the outskirts of the Andromeda Galaxy and a mass-to-light ratio of 50; in 1940, Oort discovered and wrote about the large non-visible halo of NGC 3115.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The hypothesis of dark matter largely took root in the 1970s.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Several different observations were synthesized to argue that galaxies should be surrounded by halos of unseen matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] In two papers that appeared in 1974, this conclusion was drawn in tandem by independent groups: in Princeton, New Jersey, by Jeremiah Ostriker, Jim Peebles, and Amos Yahil, and in Tartu, Estonia, by Jaan Einasto, Enn Saar, and Ants Kaasik.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] One of the observations that served as evidence for the existence of galactic halos of dark matter was the shape of galaxy rotation curves.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] These observations were done in optical and radio astronomy.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] In optical astronomy, Vera Rubin and Kent Ford worked with a new spectrograph to measure the velocity curve of edge-on spiral galaxies with greater accuracy.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] At the same time, radio astronomers were making use of new radio telescopes to map the 21 cm line of atomic hydrogen in nearby galaxies.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The radial distribution of interstellar atomic hydrogen (HI) often extends to much greater galactic distances than can be observed as collective starlight, expanding the sampled distances for rotation curves – and thus of the total mass distribution – to a new dynamical regime.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Early mapping of the Andromeda Galaxy with the 300-foot (91 m) telescope at Green Bank and the 250-foot (76 m) dish at Jodrell Bank already showed the HI rotation curve did not trace the decline expected from Keplerian orbits.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] As more sensitive receivers became available, Roberts & Whitehurst (1975) were able to trace the rotational velocity of Andromeda to 30 kpc, much beyond the optical measurements.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] In parallel, the use of interferometric arrays for extragalactic HI spectroscopy was being developed.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Rogstad & Shostak (1972) published HI rotation curves of five spirals mapped with the Owens Valley interferometer; the rotation curves of all five were very flat, suggesting very large values of mass-to-light ratio in the outer parts of their extended HI disks.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] In 1978, Albert Bosma showed further evidence of flat rotation curves using data from the Westerbork Synthesis Radio Telescope.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] By decoupling the analysis from specific neutrino properties and treating the candidate generically, the authors set out a framework that later became the standard template for weakly interacting massive particles (WIMPs) and for comparing particle-physics models with cosmological constraints.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Though subsequent work has refined the methodology and explored many alternative candidates, this paper marked the first explicit, systematic treatment of dark matter as a new particle species beyond the Standard Model.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] By the late 1970s the existence of dark matter halos around galaxies was widely recognized as real, and became a major unsolved problem in astronomy.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] A stream of observations in the 1980–1990s supported the presence of dark matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Persic, Salucci & Stel (1996) is notable for the investigation of 967 spirals.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The evidence for dark matter also included gravitational lensing of background objects by galaxy clusters, the temperature distribution of hot gas in galaxies and clusters, and the pattern of anisotropies in the cosmic microwave background.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Since the turn of the millennium, the search for particle dark matter has been dominated by the hypothesis of weakly interacting massive particles (WIMPs), driven by hypothesized connections to supersymmetry.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Experimental efforts were characterized by a rapid increase in sensitivity using liquid xenon detectors, including XENON, LUX, PandaX, and LUX-ZEPLIN (LZ).
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Despite pushing interaction limits down by orders of magnitude, these direct detection experiments all reported null results for WIMPs across the standard GeV–TeV mass range.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Concurrently, the failure of the Large Hadron Collider to detect supersymmetric particles has constrained the theoretical parameter space for WIMPs.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] These constraints have shifted significant focus toward alternative candidates such as axions.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The Axion Dark Matter Experiment achieved sensitivity to the plausible DFSZ axion model in the micro-electronvolt range by the early 2020s.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The prevailing view among cosmologists remains that dark matter is composed primarily of some type of not-yet-characterized subatomic particle.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] While this remains the majority opinion, the lack of particle detection has led to a divergence in consensus, with macroscopic candidates such as primordial black holes seeing renewed interest following observations by LIGO and the James Webb Space Telescope.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The search for such particles, by a variety of means, is one of the major efforts in particle physics.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] In standard cosmological calculations, *"matter"* means any constituent of the universe whose energy density scales with the inverse cube of the scale factor, i.e., *ρ* ∝ *a*−3 .
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] This is in contrast to *"radiation"*, which scales as the inverse fourth power of the scale factor *ρ* ∝ *a*−4 , and a cosmological constant, which does not change with respect to a (*ρ* ∝ *a*0).
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The different scaling factors for matter and radiation are a consequence of radiation redshift.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] For example, after doubling the diameter of the observable Universe via cosmic expansion, the scale, a, has doubled.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The energy of the cosmic microwave background radiation has been halved (because the wavelength of each photon has doubled); the energy of ultra-relativistic particles, such as early-era standard-model neutrinos, is similarly halved.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The cosmological constant, as an intrinsic property of space, has a constant energy density regardless of the volume under consideration.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] In principle, "dark matter" means all components of the universe which are not visible but still obey *ρ* ∝ *a*−3 .
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] In practice, the term "dark matter" is often used to mean only the non-baryonic component of dark matter, i.e., excluding "missing baryons".
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Context will usually indicate which meaning is intended.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The arms of spiral galaxies rotate around their galactic center.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The luminous mass density of a spiral galaxy decreases as one goes from the center to the outskirts.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] If luminous mass were all the matter, then the galaxy can be modelled as a point mass in the centre and test masses orbiting around it, similar to the Solar System.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] From Kepler's Third Law, it is expected that the rotation velocities will decrease with distance from the center, similar to the Solar System.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Instead, the galaxy rotation curve remains flat or even increases as distance from the center increases.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] If Kepler's laws are correct, then the obvious way to resolve this discrepancy is to conclude the mass distribution in spiral galaxies is not similar to that of the Solar System.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] In particular, there may be a lot of non-luminous matter (dark matter) in the outskirts of the galaxy.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Stars in bound systems must obey the virial theorem.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The theorem, together with the measured velocity distribution, can be used to measure the mass distribution in a bound system, such as elliptical galaxies or globular clusters.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] With some exceptions, velocity dispersion estimates of elliptical galaxies do not match the predicted velocity dispersion from the observed mass distribution, even assuming complicated distributions of stellar orbits.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] As with galaxy rotation curves, the obvious way to resolve the discrepancy is to postulate the existence of non-luminous matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Generally, these three methods are in reasonable agreement that dark matter outweighs visible matter by approximately 5 to 1.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] On larger scales, large galaxy redshift surveys may be used to make a three-dimensional map of the galaxy distribution.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] These maps are slightly distorted because distances are estimated from observed redshifts; the redshift contains a contribution from the galaxy's so-called peculiar velocity in addition to the dominant Hubble expansion term.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] On average, superclusters are expanding more slowly than the cosmic mean due to their gravity, while voids are expanding faster than average.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] In a redshift map, galaxies in front of a supercluster have excess radial velocities towards it and have redshifts slightly higher than their distance would imply, while galaxies behind the supercluster have redshifts slightly low for their distance.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] This effect causes superclusters to appear squashed in the radial direction, and likewise voids are stretched.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] This effect is not detectable for any one structure since the true shape is not known, but can be measured by averaging over many structures.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] It was predicted quantitatively by Nick Kaiser in 1987, and first decisively measured in 2001 by the 2dF Galaxy Redshift Survey.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Results are in agreement with the Lambda-CDM model.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The bullet cluster is the result of a recent collision of two galaxy clusters.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] It is of particular note because the location of the center of mass as measured by gravitational lensing is different from the location of the center of mass of visible matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] This is difficult for modified gravity theories, which generally predict lensing around visible matter, to explain.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Standard dark matter theory however has no issue: the hot, visible gas in each cluster would be cooled and slowed down by electromagnetic interactions, while dark matter (which does not interact electromagnetically) would not.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] This leads to the dark matter separating from the visible gas, producing the separate lensing peak as observed.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] One of the consequences of general relativity is the gravitational lens.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Gravitational lensing occurs when massive objects between a source of light and the observer act as a lens to bend light from this source.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Lensing does not depend on the properties of the mass; it only requires there to be a mass.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The more massive an object, the more lensing is observed.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] An example is a cluster of galaxies lying between a more distant source such as a quasar and an observer.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] In this case, the galaxy cluster will lens the quasar.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Strong lensing is the observed distortion of background galaxies into arcs when their light passes through such a gravitational lens.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] It has been observed around many distant clusters including Abell 1689.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] By measuring the distortion geometry, the mass of the intervening cluster can be obtained.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] In the weak regime, lensing does not distort background galaxies into arcs, causing minute distortions instead.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] By examining the apparent shear deformation of the adjacent background galaxies, the mean distribution of dark matter can be characterized.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The measured mass-to-light ratios correspond to dark matter densities predicted by other large-scale structure measurements.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Type Ia supernovae can be used as standard candles to measure extragalactic distances, which can in turn be used to measure how fast the universe has expanded in the past.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Data indicates the universe is expanding at an accelerating rate, the cause of which is usually ascribed to dark energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Since observations indicate the universe is almost flat, it is expected the total energy density of everything in the universe should sum to 1 (Ωtot ≈ 1).
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The measured dark energy density is ΩΛ ≈ 0.690; the observed ordinary (baryonic) matter energy density is Ωb ≈ 0.0482 and the energy density of radiation is negligible.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] This leaves a missing Ωdm ≈ 0.258 which nonetheless behaves like matter (see technical definition section above) – dark matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] In astronomical spectroscopy, the Lyman-alpha forest is the sum of the absorption lines arising from the Lyman-alpha transition of neutral hydrogen in the spectra of distant galaxies and quasars.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Lyman-alpha forest observations can also constrain cosmological models.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] These constraints agree with those obtained from WMAP data.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Although both dark matter and ordinary matter are matter, they do not behave in the same way.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] In particular, in the early universe, ordinary matter was ionized and interacted strongly with radiation via Thomson scattering.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Dark matter does not interact directly with radiation, but it does affect the cosmic microwave background (CMB) by its gravitational potential (mainly on large scales) and by its effects on the density and velocity of ordinary matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Ordinary and dark matter perturbations, therefore, evolve differently with time and leave different imprints on the CMB.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The CMB is very close to a perfect blackbody but contains very small temperature anisotropies of a few parts in 100,000.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] A sky map of anisotropies can be decomposed into an angular power spectrum, which is observed to contain a series of acoustic peaks at near-equal spacing but different heights.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The locations of these peaks depend on cosmological parameters.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Matching theory to data, therefore, constrains cosmological parameters.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The CMB anisotropy was first discovered by COBE in 1992, though this had too coarse resolution to detect the acoustic peaks.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] After the discovery of the first acoustic peak by the balloon-borne BOOMERanG experiment in 2000, the power spectrum was precisely observed by WMAP in 2003–2012, and even more precisely by the *Planck* spacecraft in 2013–2015.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The results support the Lambda-CDM model.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The observed CMB angular power spectrum provides powerful evidence in support of dark matter, as its precise structure is well fitted by the Lambda-CDM model, but difficult to reproduce with any competing model such as modified Newtonian dynamics (MOND).
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Structure formation refers to the period after the Big Bang when density perturbations collapsed to form stars, galaxies, and clusters.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Prior to structure formation, the Friedmann solutions to general relativity describe a homogeneous universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Later, small anisotropies gradually grew and condensed the homogeneous universe into stars, galaxies and larger structures.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Ordinary matter is affected by radiation, which is the dominant element of the universe at very early times.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] As a result, its density perturbations are washed out and unable to condense into structure.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] If there were only ordinary matter in the universe, there would not have been enough time for density perturbations to grow into the galaxies and clusters currently seen.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Dark matter provides a solution to this problem because it is unaffected by radiation.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Therefore, its density perturbations can grow first.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The resulting gravitational potential acts as an attractive potential well for ordinary matter collapsing later, speeding up the structure formation process.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Baryon acoustic oscillations (BAO) are fluctuations in the density of the visible baryonic matter (normal matter) of the universe on large scales.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] These are predicted to arise in the Lambda-CDM model due to acoustic oscillations in the photon–baryon fluid of the early universe and can be observed in the cosmic microwave background angular power spectrum.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] BAOs set up a preferred length scale for baryons.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] As the dark matter and baryons clumped together after recombination, the effect is much weaker in the galaxy distribution in the nearby universe, but is detectable as a subtle (~ 1%) preference for pairs of galaxies to be separated by 147 Mpc, compared to those separated by 130–160 Mpc.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] This feature was predicted theoretically in the 1990s and then discovered in 2005, in two large galaxy redshift surveys, the Sloan Digital Sky Survey and the 2dF Galaxy Redshift Survey.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Combining the CMB observations with BAO measurements from galaxy redshift surveys provides a precise estimate of the Hubble constant and the average matter density in the Universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Dark matter can be divided into *cold*, *warm*, and *hot* categories.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] These categories refer to velocity rather than an actual temperature, and indicate how far corresponding objects moved due to random motions in the early universe, before they slowed due to cosmic expansion.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] This distance is called the *free streaming length*.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The categories of dark matter are set with respect to the size of the collection of mass prior to structure formation that later collapses to form a dwarf galaxy.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] This collection of mass is sometimes called a protogalaxy.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Dark matter particles are classified as cold, warm, or hot if their free streaming length is much smaller (cold), similar to (warm), or much larger (hot) than the protogalaxy of a dwarf galaxy.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Mixtures of the above are also possible: a theory of mixed dark matter was popular in the mid-1990s, but was rejected following the discovery of dark energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The significance of the free streaming length is that the universe began with some primordial density fluctuations from the Big Bang (in turn arising from quantum fluctuations at the microscale).
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Particles from overdense regions will naturally spread to underdense regions, but because the universe is expanding quickly, there is a time limit for them to do so.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Faster particles (hot dark matter) can beat the time limit while slower particles cannot.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The particles travel a free streaming length's worth of distance within the time limit; therefore this length sets a minimum scale for later structure formation.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Because galaxy-size density fluctuations get washed out by free-streaming, hot dark matter implies the first objects that can form are huge supercluster-size pancakes, which then fragment into galaxies, while the reverse is true for cold dark matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Deep-field observations show that galaxies formed first, followed by clusters and superclusters as galaxies clump together, and therefore that most dark matter is cold.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] This is also the reason why neutrinos, which move at nearly the speed of light and therefore would fall under hot dark matter, cannot make up the bulk of dark matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] features appearing as galaxies smeared into crescent shapes.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] JWST images show much higher sensitivity and resolution at infrared wavelengths, allowing it to see more distant, fainter objects in clearer detail.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The identity of dark matter is unknown, but there are many hypotheses about what dark matter could consist of, as set out in the table below.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Dark matter can refer to any substance which interacts predominantly via gravity with visible matter (e.g., stars and planets).
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Hence in principle it need not be composed of a new type of fundamental particle but could, at least in part, be made up of standard baryonic matter, such as protons or neutrons.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Most of the ordinary matter familiar to astronomers, including planets, brown dwarfs, red dwarfs, visible stars, white dwarfs, neutron stars, and black holes, fall into this category.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] A black hole would ingest both baryonic and non-baryonic matter that comes close enough to its event horizon; afterwards, the distinction between the two is lost.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] These massive objects that are hard to detect are collectively known as MACHOs.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Some scientists initially hoped that baryonic MACHOs could account for and explain all the dark matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] There are two main candidates for non-baryonic dark matter: new particles and primordial black holes.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Unlike baryonic matter, nonbaryonic particles do not contribute to the formation of the elements in the early universe (Big Bang nucleosynthesis) and so its presence is felt only via its gravitational effects (such as weak lensing).
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] In addition, some dark matter candidates can interact with themselves (self-interacting dark matter) or with ordinary particles (e.g.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] WIMPs), possibly resulting in observable by-products such as gamma rays and neutrinos (indirect detection).
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Candidates abound (see the table above), each with their own strengths and weaknesses.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] There exists no formal definition of a Weakly Interacting Massive Particle (WIMP), but broadly, it is an elementary particle which interacts via gravity and any other force (or forces) which is as weak as or weaker than the weak nuclear force, but also non-vanishing in strength.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Many WIMP candidates are expected to have been produced thermally in the early Universe, similarly to the particles of the Standard Model according to Big Bang cosmology, and usually will constitute cold dark matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Obtaining the correct abundance of dark matter today via thermal production requires a self-annihilation cross section of $\langle \sigma v\rangle$ ≃ 3×10−26 cm3⋅s−1, which is roughly what is expected for a new particle in the 100 GeV/*c*2 mass range that interacts via the electroweak force.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Because supersymmetric extensions of the Standard Model of particle physics readily predict a new particle with these properties, this apparent coincidence has been called the "WIMP miracle", and a stable supersymmetric partner has long been a prime explanation for dark matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] In the early 2010s, results from direct-detection experiments along with the lack of evidence for supersymmetry at the Large Hadron Collider (LHC) experiment have cast doubt on the simplest WIMP hypothesis.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Axions are hypothetical elementary particles originally theorized in 1978 independently by Frank Wilczek and Steven Weinberg as the Goldstone boson of Peccei–Quinn theory, which had been proposed in 1977 to solve the strong CP problem in quantum chromodynamics (QCD).
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] QCD effects produce an effective periodic potential in which the axion field moves.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Expanding the potential about one of its minima, one finds that the product of the axion mass with the axion decay constant is determined by the topological susceptibility of the QCD vacuum.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] An axion with mass that is much less than 60 keV/*c*2 is long-lived and weakly interacting: a perfect dark matter candidate.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The oscillations of the axion field about the minimum of the effective potential, the so-called misalignment mechanism, generate a cosmological population of cold axions with an abundance depending on the mass of the axion.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] With a mass above 5 μeV/c2 (10−11 times the electron mass) axions could account for dark matter, and thus be both a dark-matter candidate and a solution to the strong CP problem.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] If inflation occurs at a low scale and lasts sufficiently long, the axion mass can be as low as 1 peV/*c*2.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Because axions have extremely low mass, their de Broglie wavelength is very large, in turn meaning that quantum effects could help resolve the small-scale problems of the Lambda-CDM model.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] A single ultralight axion with a decay constant at the grand unified theory scale provides the correct relic density without fine-tuning.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Axions as a dark matter candidate have gained in popularity in recent years, because of the non-detection of WIMPs.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] If dark matter is composed of weakly interacting particles, then an obvious question is whether it can form objects equivalent to planets, stars, or black holes.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Ordinary matter forms dense objects because it has numerous ways to lose energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Dark matter appears to lack a means to lose energy, simply because it is not capable of interacting strongly in other ways except through gravity.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] suggests that such a particle would not stay bound to the gradually forming object – as the object began to form and compact, the dark matter particles within it would speed up and tend to escape.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Ordinary matter interacts in many different ways, which allows the matter to form more complex structures.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] , although until dark matter is better understood, this is only speculation).
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Primordial black holes (PBHs) are hypothetical black holes that formed soon after the Big Bang.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] In the inflationary era and early radiation-dominated universe, extremely dense pockets of subatomic matter may have been tightly packed to the point of gravitational collapse, creating black holes without the supernova compression typically needed to create stellar black holes.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The idea was first suggested by Yakov Zeldovich and Igor Dmitriyevich Novikov in 1966, and independently by Stephen Hawking in 1971.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Because PBHs would form prior to stellar evolution, they are non-baryonic dark matter candidates and are not limited to the narrow mass range of stellar black holes; they could range from Planck-mass relics to supermassive scales.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Interest in PBHs as a primary component of dark matter was revived following the 2015 discovery of gravitational waves by LIGO.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Their first detected merger involved black holes of approximately 30 solar masses; such objects are difficult to explain via standard stellar collapse but fit the predicted mass range for PBHs formed during the QCD transition in the early universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] This interest was bolstered in November 2025, when the LIGO/Virgo/KAGRA collaboration reported a candidate gravitational wave signal from a sub-solar mass merger.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] As no astrophysical process is known to produce black holes below the Chandrasekhar limit (~1.4 solar masses), confirmed sub-solar mass objects would be strong evidence for a primordial origin.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] As there have been no gravitational waves detected at z>1 (>6 Gya), and the sensitivity to lower-mass collisions falls off with distance, we are not currently able to detect collisions in the earliest half of the age of the universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Further support for the PBH hypothesis has emerged from James Webb Space Telescope (JWST) observations of the high-redshift universe (z > 7).
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] JWST discovered unexpected populations of "Little Red Dots" (LRDs, compact very high redshift objects) and "overmassive black hole galaxies" such as UHZ1 and GHZ2, which contain supermassive black holes appearing less than 500 million years after the Big Bang and outweighing their galaxy's stars.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] These active galactic nuclei challenge standard models of accretion from "light" stellar black hole seeds, and suggest "heavy seeds" formed via direct collapse or PBHs, which could account for a significant fraction of dark matter halos.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] However, those constraints assume all PBHs have the same mass, a monochromatic mass distribution.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] More recent analyses utilizing extended mass distributions, predicted by inflation models and evident in gravitational wave and JWST observations, remove such constraints.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] A 2024 review indicates that PBHs with a broad, platykurtic mass distribution peaking around one solar mass could explain the entirety of dark matter, or coexist with other candidates in a mixed dark matter scenario.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] The primary theoretical challenge to the PBH hypothesis is the physical mechanism of their formation.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Standard models of cosmic inflation, known as "slow-roll inflation", generate density fluctuations that are far too small to trigger primordial collapse.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Consequently, producing the required abundance of PBHs typically necessitates "exotic" inflation models, often featuring inflection points, bumps, or plateaus in the inflaton potential, which can amplify fluctuations by orders of magnitude.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] However, proponents contend that as the natural parameter space for WIMPs is increasingly excluded by null results from all detection experiments, particle dark matter theories now require comparable levels of fine-tuning.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Furthermore, proponents argue that the specific mass structures predicted by these exotic inflation models provide a unified explanation for observational anomalies seen by LIGO and JWST that particle models do not address.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] To address the fine-tuning problem, recent research has focused on mechanisms that generate the required fluctuations through natural physical processes rather than manual adjustments to the inflaton potential.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] One such mechanism is the QCD phase transition; as the universe cooled through this epoch, the reduction in the equation of state (pressure) naturally lowered the threshold for gravitational collapse.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] This effect automatically enhances the formation of black holes at the solar mass scale, comparable to those detected by gravitational wave observatories, without requiring a precisely tuned peak in the inflation power spectrum.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p01] Additionally, models involving multiple scalar fields can produce sharp spikes in density fluctuations through dynamic interactions, such as rapid turns in the field trajectory, which derive the necessary conditions from the model's geometric structure rather than from fine-tuned parameters.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] If dark matter is made up of subatomic particles, then millions, possibly billions, of such particles must pass through every square centimeter of the Earth each second.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Many experiments aim to test this hypothesis.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Although WIMPs have been the main search candidates, axions have drawn renewed attention, with the Axion Dark Matter Experiment (ADMX) searches for axions and many more planned in the future.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Another candidate is heavy hidden sector particles which only interact with ordinary matter via gravity.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] These experiments can be divided into two classes: direct detection experiments, which search for the scattering of dark matter particles off atomic nuclei within a detector; and indirect detection, which look for the products of dark matter particle annihilations or decays.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Direct detection experiments aim to observe interactions between dark matter particles passing through the Earth and ordinary matter detector targets.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] For Weakly interacting massive particles (WIMPs), the primary signature is a low-energy recoil of nuclei (typically a few keV), which induces energy in the form of scintillation light, ionization, or phonons (heat).
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] For axions, experiments typically search for the conversion of axions into photons within a strong magnetic field (the Primakoff effect).
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] To detect these rare events effectively, it is crucial to maintain an extremely low background, which is why such experiments typically operate deep underground where interference from cosmic rays is minimized.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Major underground laboratories hosting these experiments include SNOLAB (Canada), LNGS (Italy), CJPL (China), and the SURF (USA).
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] WIMP searches mostly use either cryogenic or noble liquid detector technologies.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Cryogenic detectors, operating at temperatures below 100 mK, detect the heat produced when a particle hits an atom in a crystal absorber such as germanium.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Experiments using this technology include SuperCDMS and EDELWEISS.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Noble liquid detectors detect scintillation and ionization produced by a particle collision in liquid xenon or argon.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] This technology has led the field in sensitivity for the last decade.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Major current experiments include LZ (at SURF), XENONnT (at LNGS), and PandaX-4T (at CJPL), with future argon-based projects like DarkSide-20k in development.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] As of late 2025, there has been no confirmed detection of dark matter from these standard WIMP searches.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Instead, experiments have placed strong upper limits on the particle's interaction cross-section with nucleons.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] In late 2025, the LZ experiment reported the exclusion of WIMP cross-sections above 9 GeV/c2 and the first detection of boron-8 solar neutrinos via coherent elastic neutrino-nucleus scattering in a dark matter detector.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] This was the first experimental entry into the "neutrino fog", an irreducible background of neutrino interactions that mimics dark matter signals and complicates future WIMP searches.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] As WIMP parameter space has become increasingly constrained, focus has also shifted toward axion searches.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] These experiments, such as the Axion Dark Matter Experiment, typically use resonant microwave cavities rather than nuclear recoil targets.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] By the early 2020s, ADMX had achieved sensitivity to the plausible DFSZ axion model in the micro-electronvolt range.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Despite the null results from major noble liquid and cryogenic experiments, the DAMA/NaI and DAMA/LIBRA collaborations have famously observed an annual modulation in their event rate, which they claim is due to the Earth's motion through the dark matter halo.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] This claim remains in tension with the negative results from the more sensitive experiments (LZ, XENON, SuperCDMS) described above.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] A special case of direct detection involves directional sensitivity, which attempts to correlate WIMP signals with the direction of the Solar System's motion towards Cygnus.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Directional experiments using low-pressure time projection chambers include DMTPC, DRIFT, CYGNUS, and MIMAC.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Indirect detection experiments search for the products of the self-annihilation or decay of dark matter particles in outer space.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] For example, in regions of high dark matter density (e.g., the centre of the Milky Way) two dark matter particles could annihilate to produce gamma rays or Standard Model particle–antiparticle pairs.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Alternatively, if a dark matter particle is unstable, it could decay into Standard Model (or other) particles.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] These processes could be detected indirectly through an excess of gamma rays, antiprotons or positrons emanating from high density regions in the Milky Way and other galaxies.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] A major difficulty inherent in such searches is that various astrophysical sources can mimic the signal expected from dark matter, and so multiple signals are likely required for a conclusive discovery.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] A few of the dark matter particles passing through the Sun or Earth may scatter off atoms and lose energy.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Thus dark matter may accumulate at the center of these bodies, increasing the chance of collision/annihilation.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] This could produce a distinctive signal in the form of high-energy neutrinos.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Such a signal would be strong indirect proof of WIMP dark matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] High-energy neutrino telescopes such as AMANDA, IceCube and ANTARES are searching for this signal.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] The detection by LIGO in September 2015 of gravitational waves opens the possibility of observing dark matter in a new way, particularly if it is in the form of primordial black holes.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Beyond searching for annihilation products, astrophysicists are using celestial objects as natural detectors to constrain dark matter particle properties.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] An alternative approach to the detection of dark matter particles in nature is to produce them in a laboratory.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Experiments with the Large Hadron Collider (LHC) may be able to detect dark matter particles produced in collisions of the LHC proton beams.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Because a dark matter particle should have negligible interactions with normal visible matter, it may be detected indirectly as large amounts of missing energy and momentum that escape the detectors, provided other non-negligible collision products are detected.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] For decades, the leading candidate for dark matter was the lightest neutralino predicted by supersymmetry.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] However, extensive searches through the conclusion of the LHC's run 3 (2022–2025) operations have failed to detect the superpartners (such as squarks and gluinos) predicted by supersymmetry models.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] By late 2025, the ATLAS and CMS collaborations had pushed exclusion limits for gluinos beyond 2.4 TeV, and limits for charginos and neutralinos ("electroweak-inos") beyond 1 TeV in many scenarios.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] This persistent absence has ruled out the most favored parameter space for WIMPs, forcing theorists to consider more complex and fine-tuned models such as "split supersymmetry", or to abandon supersymmetry candidates entirely.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] In response to these null results, experimental focus has shifted toward "dark sector" theories and more exotic signatures that might have evaded earlier experiments.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] If dark matter is not an undiscovered particle, then the next possibility is that general relativity, the theory underpinning modern cosmology, is incorrect.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] General relativity is well-tested on Solar System scales, but its validity on galactic or cosmological scales has not been well proven.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] A suitable modification to general relativity can conceivably eliminate the need for dark matter.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] The best-known theories of this class are modified Newtonian dynamics (MOND) and its relativistic generalization tensor–vector–scalar gravity (TeVeS), f(R) gravity, negative mass, dark fluid, entropic gravity, conformal gravity, and massive gravity.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] A problem with modifying gravity is that observational evidence for dark matter – let alone general relativity – comes from so many independent approaches (see § Observational evidence above).
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Explaining any individual observation is possible but explaining all of them in the absence of dark matter is very difficult.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Nonetheless, there have been some scattered successes for alternative hypotheses, such as a 2016 test of gravitational lensing in entropic gravity and a 2020 measurement of a unique MOND effect.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] The prevailing opinion among most astrophysicists is that while modifications to general relativity can conceivably explain part of the observational evidence, there is probably enough data to conclude there must be some form of dark matter present in the universe.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] While WIMPs, axions, and primordial black holes remain the primary candidates for dark matter, numerous other theories have been proposed to address specific observational anomalies or theoretical motivations.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] These alternative models often explore mass ranges and interaction strengths outside the standard parameter space, ranging from ultra-light scalar fields to massive composite states.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Some hypotheses posit the existence of complex "dark sectors" with their own fundamental forces, while others suggest that dark matter may be unstable, dynamical, or composed of mirror particles.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] The following list encompasses these less established but theoretically motivated candidates and frameworks.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Dark matter regularly appears as a topic in hybrid periodicals that cover both factual scientific topics and science fiction, and dark matter itself has been referred to as "the stuff of science fiction".
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] Mention of dark matter is made in works of fiction.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] In such cases, it is usually attributed extraordinary physical or magical properties, thus becoming inconsistent with the hypothesized properties of dark matter in physics and cosmology.
[src:cosmology/dark-matter-p02] More broadly, the phrase "dark matter" is used metaphorically in fiction to evoke the unseen or invisible.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The **expansion of the universe** is the increase in distance between gravitationally unbound parts of the observable universe with time.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] It is an intrinsic expansion, so it does not mean that the universe expands into anything or that space exists outside it.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] To any observer in the universe, it appears that all but the nearest galaxies (which are bound to each other by gravity) move away at speeds that are proportional to their distance from the observer, on average.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] While objects cannot move faster than light, this limitation applies only with respect to local reference frames and does not limit the recession rates of cosmologically distant objects.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The expansion of the universe was discovered by separate theoretical and observational work in the 1920s.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Since then, the expansion has become a core aspect of the astrophysical field of cosmology.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Many major scientific projects have sought to characterize the expansion and understand its effects.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Cosmic expansion is a key feature of Big Bang cosmology.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Within the theory of general relativity, it is modeled mathematically with the Friedmann–Lemaître–Robertson–Walker (FLRW) metric.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The consensus or "standard" model of cosmology, the Lambda-CDM model, hypothesizes different expansion rates during different times, depending on the physical properties of the contents of spacetime.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The very earliest expansion, called inflation, saw the universe suddenly expand by a factor of at least 1026 in every direction about 10−32 of a second after the Big Bang.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Cosmic expansion subsequently decelerated to much slower rates, until around 9.8 billion years after the Big Bang (4 billion years ago) it began to gradually expand more quickly, and is still doing so.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Physicists have postulated the existence of dark energy, appearing as a cosmological constant in the simplest gravitational models, as a way to explain this late-time acceleration which is predicted to be dominant in the future.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The concept of the expansion of the universe is difficult to explain, leading to several misconceptions about its nature, origin, and effects.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] In 1912–1914, Vesto Slipher discovered that light from remote galaxies was redshifted, a phenomenon later interpreted as galaxies receding from the Earth.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] In 1922, Alexander Friedmann used the Einstein field equations to provide theoretical evidence that the universe is expanding.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The key astronomical demonstration of the expansion of the universe is known as Hubble's law or sometimes as the Hubble–Lemaître law.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The name and thus the honor of the discovery has been debated.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] In 1924, Swedish astronomer Knut Lundmark found observational evidence for expansion.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] While his results were reasonably accurate even by today's standards, they relied upon galaxy diameter measurements and the distance to the Andromeda Galaxy which were unproven at the time.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] In 1927, Georges Lemaître derived solutions for Einstein's equations of general relativity and applied them to data published by Slipher and Hubble to propose a linear relationship between distance to galaxies and their recessional velocity.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The linear relationship was firmly established by Edwin Hubble in 1929 using multiple methods and cross-checked with proven techniques.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Astronomer Walter Baade recalculated the size of the known universe in the 1940s, doubling the previous value.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] For most of the second half of the 20th century, the value of the Hubble constant was estimated to be between 50 and 90 km⋅s−1⋅Mpc−1.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] On 13 January 1994, NASA formally announced a completion of its repairs related to the main mirror of the Hubble Space Telescope, allowing for sharper images and, consequently, more accurate analyses of its observations.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Shortly after the repairs were made, Wendy Freedman's 1994 Key Project analyzed the recession velocity of M100 from the core of the Virgo Cluster, offering a Hubble constant measurement of 80±17 km⋅s−1⋅Mpc−1.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Later the same year, Adam Riess et al. used an empirical method of visual-band light-curve shapes to more finely estimate the luminosity of Type Ia supernovae.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] This further minimized the systematic measurement errors of the Hubble constant, to 67±7 km⋅s−1⋅Mpc−1.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Reiss's measurements on the recession velocity of the nearby Virgo Cluster more closely agree with subsequent and independent analyses of Cepheid variable calibrations of Type Ia supernovae, which estimates a Hubble constant of 73±7 km⋅s−1⋅Mpc−1.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] In 2003, David Spergel's analysis of the cosmic microwave background during the first year observations of the *Wilkinson Microwave Anisotropy Probe* satellite (WMAP) further agreed with the estimated expansion rates for local galaxies, 72±5 km⋅s−1⋅Mpc−1.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Distant galaxies in all directions are observed to move away from Earth and their velocity is proportional to their distance from Earth.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] This observation, known as Hubble's law, combined with the observation that the universe at the largest scales is homogeneous (the same everywhere) and isotropic (the same in all directions), means that the universe is expanding uniformly at the present time.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] This means the distance between any two galaxies increases over time by the same factor.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] where the Hubble constant $H_{0}$ quantifies the rate of expansion today.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] While the expansion in space is uniform, it is not uniform across long time intervals: the rate of expansion varies with time and this variation is a central object of study in cosmology.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Using cosmic time with $t_{0}$ indicating the present, the Hubble constant, $H_{0}=H(t=t_{0})$ , is the present day value of the Hubble parameter, $H(t)$ , describing the dynamics of expansion.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The expansion of the universe can be understood as resulting from an initial condition in which the contents of the universe are flying apart.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The mutual gravitational attraction of the matter and radiation within the universe gradually slows this expansion over time, but their density is too low to prevent continued expansion.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] In addition, recent observational evidence suggests that dark energy is now accelerating the expansion.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Mathematically, the expansion of the universe is quantified by the scale factor, a , which is proportional to the average separation between objects, such as galaxies.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The scale factor is a function of time and is conventionally set to be $a=1$ at the present time.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Because the universe is expanding, a is smaller in the past and larger in the future.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Extrapolating back in time with certain cosmological models will yield a moment when the scale factor was zero; our current understanding of cosmology sets this time at 13.787 ± 0.020 billion years ago.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] If the universe continues to expand forever, the scale factor will approach infinity in the future.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] It is also possible in principle for the universe to stop expanding and begin to contract, which corresponds to the scale factor decreasing in time.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The scale factor a is a parameter of the FLRW metric, and its time evolution is governed by the Friedmann equations.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] shows how the contents of the universe influence its expansion rate.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Here, G is the gravitational constant, $\rho$ is the energy density within the universe, p is the pressure, c is the speed of light, and $\Lambda$ is the cosmological constant.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] A positive energy density leads to deceleration of the expansion, ${\ddot {a}}<0$ , and a positive pressure further decelerates expansion.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] On the other hand, sufficiently negative pressure with $p<-\rho c^{2}/3$ leads to accelerated expansion, and the cosmological constant also accelerates expansion.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Nonrelativistic matter is essentially pressureless, with $|p|\ll \rho c^{2}$ , while a gas of ultrarelativistic particles (such as a photon gas) has positive pressure $p=\rho c^{2}/3$ .
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Negative-pressure fluids, like dark energy, are not experimentally confirmed, but the existence of dark energy is inferred from astronomical observations.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] In an expanding universe, it is often useful to study the evolution of structure with the expansion of the universe factored out.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] This motivates the use of comoving coordinates, which are defined to grow proportionally with the scale factor.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] If an object is moving only with the Hubble flow of the expanding universe, with no other motion, then it remains stationary in comoving coordinates.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The comoving coordinates are the spatial coordinates in the FLRW metric.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The universe is a four-dimensional spacetime, but within a universe that obeys the cosmological principle, there is a natural choice of three-dimensional spatial surface.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] These are the surfaces on which observers who are stationary in comoving coordinates agree on the age of the universe.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] In a universe governed by special relativity, such surfaces would be hyperboloids, because relativistic time dilation means that rapidly receding distant observers' clocks are slowed, so that spatial surfaces must bend "into the future" over long distances.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] However, within general relativity, the shape of these *comoving synchronous* spatial surfaces is affected by gravity.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Current observations are consistent with these spatial surfaces being geometrically flat (so that, for example, the angles of a triangle add up to 180 degrees).
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] An expanding universe typically has a finite age.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Light, and other particles, can have propagated only a finite distance.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The comoving distance that such particles can have covered over the age of the universe is known as the particle horizon, and the region of the universe that lies within our particle horizon is known as the observable universe.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] If the dark energy that is inferred to dominate the universe today is a cosmological constant, then the particle horizon converges to a finite value in the infinite future.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] This implies that the amount of the universe that we will ever be able to observe is limited.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Many systems exist whose light can never reach us, because there is a cosmic event horizon induced by the repulsive gravity of the dark energy.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Within the study of the evolution of structure within the universe, a natural scale emerges, known as the Hubble horizon.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Cosmological perturbations much larger than the Hubble horizon are not dynamical, because gravitational influences do not have time to propagate across them, while perturbations much smaller than the Hubble horizon are straightforwardly governed by Newtonian gravitational dynamics.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] For photons, expansion leads to the cosmological redshift.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] While the cosmological redshift is often explained as the stretching of photon wavelengths due to "expansion of space", it is more naturally viewed as a consequence of the Doppler effect.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] An object's peculiar velocity is its velocity with respect to the comoving coordinate grid, i.e., with respect to the average expansion-associated motion of the surrounding material.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] It is a measure of how a particle's motion deviates from the Hubble flow of the expanding universe.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The peculiar velocities of nonrelativistic particles decay as the universe expands, in inverse proportion with the cosmic scale factor.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] This can be understood as a self-sorting effect.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] A particle that is moving in some direction gradually overtakes the Hubble flow of cosmic expansion in that direction, asymptotically approaching material with the same velocity as its own.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] More generally, the peculiar momenta of both relativistic and nonrelativistic particles decay in inverse proportion with the scale factor.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] This follows from the decay of particles' peculiar momenta, as discussed above.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] It can also be understood as adiabatic cooling.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The temperature of ultrarelativistic fluids, often called "radiation" and including the cosmic microwave background, scales inversely with the scale factor (i.e. $T\propto a^{-1}$ ).
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The temperature of nonrelativistic matter drops more sharply, scaling as the inverse square of the scale factor (i.e. $T\propto a^{-2}$ ).
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The contents of the universe dilute as it expands.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The number of particles within a comoving volume remains fixed (on average), while the volume expands.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] For nonrelativistic matter, this implies that the energy density drops as $\rho \propto a^{-3}$ , where a is the scale factor.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] For ultrarelativistic particles ("radiation"), the energy density drops more sharply, as $\rho \propto a^{-4}$ .
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] This is because the energy of an ultrarelativistic particle is dominated by its momentum, rather than its rest mass energy (see energy-momentum relation).
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Consequently, in addition to the volume dilution of the particle count, the energy of each particle also drops in proportion with $a^{-1}$ as its peculiar momentum decays.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] In general, we can consider a perfect fluid with pressure $p=w\rho$ , where $\rho$ is the energy density.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The parameter w is the equation of state parameter.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Nonrelativistic matter has $w=0$ while radiation has $w=1/3$ .
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] For an exotic fluid with negative pressure, like dark energy, the energy density drops more slowly; if $w=-1$ it remains constant in time.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] If $w<-1$ , corresponding to phantom energy, the energy density grows as the universe expands.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Inflation is a period of accelerated expansion hypothesized to have occurred at a time of around 10−32 seconds.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] It would have been driven by the inflaton, a field that has a positive-energy false vacuum state.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Inflation was originally proposed to explain the absence of exotic relics predicted by grand unified theories, such as magnetic monopoles, because the rapid expansion would have diluted such relics.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] It was subsequently realized that the accelerated expansion would also solve the horizon problem and the flatness problem.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Additionally, quantum fluctuations during inflation would have created initial variations in the density of the universe, which gravity later amplified to yield the observed spectrum of matter density variations.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] During inflation, the cosmic scale factor grew exponentially in time.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] In order to solve the horizon and flatness problems, inflation must have lasted long enough that the scale factor grew by at least a factor of e60 (about 1026).
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The history of the universe after inflation but before a time of about 1 second is largely unknown.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] However, the universe is known to have been dominated by ultrarelativistic Standard Model particles, conventionally called *radiation*, by the time of neutrino decoupling at about 1 second.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] During radiation domination, cosmic expansion decelerated, with the scale factor growing proportionally with the square root of the time.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Since radiation redshifts as the universe expands, eventually nonrelativistic matter came to dominate the energy density of the universe.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] In the standard model, the transition happened about 50,000 years after the Big Bang.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] During the matter-dominated epoch, cosmic expansion also decelerated, with the scale factor growing as the 2/3 power of the time ( $a\propto t^{2/3}$ ).
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Also, gravitational structure formation is most efficient when nonrelativistic matter dominates, and this epoch is responsible for the formation of galaxies and the large-scale structure of the universe.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Around 3 billion years ago, at a time of about 11 billion years, dark energy is believed to have begun to dominate the energy density of the universe.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] This transition came about because dark energy does not dilute as the universe expands, instead maintaining a constant energy density.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Similarly to inflation, dark energy drives accelerated expansion, such that the scale factor grows exponentially in time.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The most direct way to measure the expansion rate is to independently measure the recession velocities and the distances of distant objects, such as galaxies.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The ratio between these quantities gives the Hubble rate, in accordance with Hubble's law.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Typically, the distance is measured using a standard candle, which is an object or event for which the intrinsic brightness is known.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The object's distance can then be inferred from the observed apparent brightness.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Meanwhile, the recession speed is measured through the redshift.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Hubble used this approach for his original measurement of the expansion rate, by measuring the brightness of Cepheid variable stars and the redshifts of their host galaxies.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] More recently, using Type Ia supernovae, the expansion rate was measured to be *H*0 = 73.24±1.74 (km/s)/Mpc.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] This means that for every million parsecs of distance from the observer, recessional velocity of objects at that distance increases by about 73 kilometres per second (160,000 mph).
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Supernovae are observable at such great distances that the light travel time therefrom can approach the age of the universe.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Consequently, they can be used to measure not only the present-day expansion rate but also the expansion history.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] In work that was awarded the 2011 Nobel Prize in Physics, supernova observations were used to determine that cosmic expansion is accelerating in the present epoch.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] By assuming a cosmological model, e.g. the Lambda-CDM model, another possibility is to infer the present-day expansion rate from the sizes of the largest fluctuations seen in the cosmic microwave background.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] A higher expansion rate would imply a smaller characteristic size of CMB fluctuations, and vice versa.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] The Planck collaboration measured the expansion rate this way and determined *H*0 = 67.4±0.5 (km/s)/Mpc.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] There is a disagreement between this measurement and the supernova-based measurements, known as the Hubble tension.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] Another independent measurement technique relies on time-delay cosmography via strong gravitational lensing.
[src:cosmology/expansion-of-the-universe] When a massive foreground object, such as a galaxy, lies directly between the observer and a distant, variable light source (such as a quasar) or a transient (such as a supernova), its gravity bends the incoming light to create multiple images of the background object.
